EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system moved from northern Old Mexico into New Mexico Wednesday night, January 27th, 2010.  This winter system then plowed east-northeast through Kansas, Texas and Oklahoma Thursday and early Friday, January 28th and 29th.  This brought significant snowfall to much of southwest and south central Kansas.  The precipitation began as light snow late Wednesday night, then picked up and continued as heavy snow for much of Thursday and Thursday night.  While snow persisted Friday morning, January 29th, in parts of our southeastern CWA, not much additional accumulation occurred.  Reports received Friday morning, January 29th, revealed a 5 to 20 mile wide swath of 7 to 11 inches of snowfall fell along an axis from near Hudson in northeastern Stafford County, to north of Haviland in Kiowa County, through northern parts of both Ford and Gray Counties, to just north of Big Bow in extreme northeastern Stanton County.  On either side of this heavy band of snow, an area of 4 to 6 inches of snow fell, basically south of a line from Shallow Water in southeast Scott County to Brownell in northeast Ness County to Pfeifer in southeast Ellis County, as well as north of a line from Elkhart in southeast Morton County to near Ashland in Clark county to near Sawyer in southeastern Pratt County.  In northern parts of DDC���s CWA, as well as in southeastern parts, 2 to 4 inches of snow fell.  The highest snowfall report received from this event was 11 inches at Ingalls in Gray County, with drifts as high as 5 feet in the Dodge City area also reported.  Winds during the event were from the north to northwest at 20 to 35 mph, which caused many areas of deep drifting and widespread travel problems.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 6.4 inches was reported 8 miles north of Jetmore.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very warm and unstable air mass developed across the region on January 20th.  This air mass was accompanied by unusually high dewpoint values for late January with ambient temperatures approaching the 70 degree mark.  A very strong and vigorous storm system moved out of the Great Basin and into the Southern Plains and Lower Mississippi Valley during the late afternoon and evening hours of January 20th.  Wind shear throughout the atmosphere was very strong and supportive of strong to severe thunderstorms.  Low level wind shear was significant enough such that super cell thunderstorms developed across the region, producing tornadoes, large hail and damaging wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A NWS storm survey team determined that the damage near Harleton, Texas was consistent with a short lived tornado.  Two brick buildings sustained minor roof and structural damage, and a grocery store sustained some roof and awning damage.  Several trees were also uprooted.

A large and very moist Pacific storm system brought widespread heavy precipitation to Utah over a five day period. The storm pulled a continuous stream of tropical moisture ahead of it and, combined with numerous embedded shortwaves, resulted in almost non-stop rainfall across many of the lower elevations and wet, heavy snow in the mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Ben Lomond Peak SNOTEL received 9.00 inches of liquid equivalent precipitation, or approximately 65 inches of snow based on snow ratios at similar elevations. Snowbasin Resort also reported 43 inches of new snow for the event.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mid level trough moved across central North Carolina and interacted with a moist and unstable atmosphere and spawned isolated to scattered showers and thunderstorms across the area during the afternoon into the early evening. A few of these storms became strong to severe, with flash flooding and damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Auto Recyclers was destroyed by a fire when lightning struck the business.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: New snowfall varying from 3 to 7 inches, previous snow cover, and northwest winds gusting to over 40 mph combined to produce widespread blowing and drifting snow in extreme northeast Nebraska. The worst conditions, with widespread visibilities below a quarter mile, were in Dixon County, with only slightly better conditions in Dakota County, where the lowest visibilities were observed more locally. Travel was brought to a standstill during the worst conditions. Even where visibilities were a little higher, travel was extremely difficult and dangerous because of the snowfall, drifting snow, and dangerous wind chills that accompanied the storm. The storm forced the closing of schools and businesses, and postponement of athletic events and other activities. The snow, blowing snow, and blizzard conditions took place on January 6th and 7th, while dangerous wind chills continued well into January 8th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Persistent north to northwest winds combined with very cold air to produce wind chill values the frequently dropped to 35 below zero or a little colder. These extremely dangerous wind chills added to the hazards produced by the preceding winter storm. As winds slowly subsided during the night of January 7th, temperatures continued to drop to well below zero, keeping the wind chills at the very dangerous level through the morning of January 8th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold high pressure settled across Deep South Texas on the evening of January 9th, continuing through the early morning of January 10th.  Clear skies and light winds allowed temperatures to fall rapidly back into the 30s after sunset. After midnight, sheltered or wind protected locations plummeted into the upper teens to lower 20s - another hard freeze - while locations with a continuing 4 to 8 mph northerly wind fell to or just below freezing for several hours. Higher relatively humidity allowed widespread frost to form, thickest in hollows and other low lying areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Clear, calm conditions allowed temperatures to plummet after sunset on the 9th across the Rio Grande Plains of Zapata County, reaching the freezing point by mid evening on its way down to near 20 degrees in rural pockets, and 20 to 25 degrees elsewhere, by daybreak on the 10th.  Temperatures touched 19 at Zapata County Airport in Medina and fell to 25 near Escobas; freezing temperatures lasted up to 10 and one half hours, with a hard freeze, or temperatures below 28 degrees, lasting between 4 and 8 hours in most areas.||Crop damage, particularly to grazing land, was not reported as of this writing.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of surface low pressure formed over south central North Dakota on the evening of the 20th and tracked into central Minnesota by mid morning of the 21st. This helped spread a swath of 6 to 8 inches of snow from Devils Lake to Reynolds (North Dakota) to Mahnomen (Minnesota). Lesser amounts of snow fell to the north and south of this line, but some areas did pick up a little light freezing drizzle.

Record Snowfall occurred across the greater Burlington area on January 2nd into January 3rd.||A powerful ocean storm southeast of Nova Scotia during the late afternoon of January 2nd, retrograded into the Gulf of Maine near Rockport, Maine by the morning of January 3rd and then proceeded to return to the Atlantic Ocean during the afternoon of January 3rd.||Wraparound snows moved into northern Vermont during the afternoon and evening hours of January 2nd and continued through the afternoon of January 3rd. The windward side (west) of the various mountain ranges in Vermont witnessed the heaviest snowfall due to upslope conditions with the leeward side (east) received less snow due to downslope. In addition, some training of mesoscale snow bands, likely a result of upslope and convergence within the Champlain Valley of Vermont accounted for record snowfall in the Burlington area. ||Favorable upslope regions received 8 to 18 inches of snowfall with over 30 inches in the greater Burlington area. Meanwhile downslope regions received 2 to 6 inches of snowfall. In addition, brisk northwest winds of 15 to 25 mph with higher gusts caused considerable blowing and drfiting of the snow with 4 to 5 foot snow drifts reported.||A record 33.1 inches of snow fell with this storm at Burlington Int'l Airport in South Burlington, which surpassed the old record of 29.8 inches that occurred on December 25-28 in 1969. ||Some other specific snowfall totals; 30 inches in Essex Junction and Colchester (Chittenden county), 25 inches in Monkton (Addison county) and Milton (Chittenden county), 24 inches in Charlotte (Chittenden county), 22 inches in Jeffersonville (Lamoille county), Underhill and Jericho (Chittenden county), 18 inches in Canaan (Essex county) and Sheldon Springs (Franklin county), 16 inches in Cambridge (Lamoille county), 14 inches in Barton (Orleans county), Danby (Rutland county) and Lincoln (Addison county).

A strong low pressure system moved across the Great Lakes into Ontario and northern Quebec on January 25th. The combination of this low pressure and relatively strong high pressure near Nova Scotia produced a strong pressure gradient. ||This resulted in strong and locally damaging south to southeast winds along the western slope communities of the Green Mountains in Vermont. Several reports of downed trees and damaged power lines with several thousand power outages. Some observed wind gusts included; 68 mph in Jeffersonville (Lamoille county), 62 mph in Jericho (Chittenden).
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several reports of downed trees and large branches in Sheldon Springs, Richford and  Montgomery.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Light to moderate snow fell across the region February 9th into early February 10th as an intensifying area of low pressure tracked northeastward from the Tennessee Valley into northern Ohio. Snowfall totals generally ranged between 6 and 10 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A steady light to moderate snow fell February 9th into early February 10th with snowfall totals ranging between 5 and 7 inches across the county.  The emergency manager reported 6.5 inches of total snow accumulation in Monticello.  Winds of 15 to 25 mph allowed for some blowing and drifting of the snow.  The accumulating snow and wind led to slide-offs and accidents, with many schools closing across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On January 6th and 7th 2010, a potent storm system moved across the region. This storm brought widespread snowfall of 3 to 6 inches to eastern Kansas and much of the northern half of Missouri. The storm system also brought bitterly cold temperatures, strong northwesterly winds and brutal wind chills to the area. Northwest winds of around 20 to 25 mph and gusts to around 35 mph were common across the region Thursday afternoon, creating significant blowing and drifting snow. These winds combined with temperatures in the single digits and lower teens, to produce wind chill values of -5 to -15 degrees during the daytime hours Thursday. ||The wind gradually decreased through Friday, as the storm system moved northeast of the region. Very cold temperatures overspread the area behind the storm system. Temperatures Friday morning ranged from 5 to -5 degrees, with Friday afternoon readings mainly in the 5 to 10 degree range.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Up to 5 inches of snow was reported across the county. Strong gusty northwest winds caused blowing and drifting snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On December 24th, Christmas Eve, a low pressure system traversed along the Gulf Of Mexico. Moisture streamed up into the area but the Jackson CWA was spared  the heavier snowfall as that occurred further east. The event was worthy of Winter Weather Advisories with a Winter Storm Warning issued for the higher elevations in Harlan and Letcher counties. A powerful east coast low pressure developed and traveled up the east coast. The fully developed low pressure system brought northerly flow into eastern Kentucky and created an extended upslope event. The event prompted the continuance of the advisories and winter storm warnings into December 27th till noon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Five inches of snow had fallen in Virgie since Friday night.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A dynamic storm system moved out of Southern Canada and across the Billings Forecast Area on the 5th and 6th of January. Ahead of the system, cold arctic air surged southward across the area. Moist air forced over this arctic air resulted in periods of heavy snowfall. In addition, gusty northerly winds created considerable blowing and drifting snow along with bitterly cold wind chills.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Judith Gap reported 3 inches of snow with visibilities 1/4 mile as a result of blowing snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system moved from northern Old Mexico into New Mexico Wednesday night, January 27th, 2010.  This winter system then plowed east-northeast through Kansas, Texas and Oklahoma Thursday and early Friday, January 28th and 29th.  This brought significant snowfall to much of southwest and south central Kansas.  The precipitation began as light snow late Wednesday night, then picked up and continued as heavy snow for much of Thursday and Thursday night.  While snow persisted Friday morning, January 29th, in parts of our southeastern CWA, not much additional accumulation occurred.  Reports received Friday morning, January 29th, revealed a 5 to 20 mile wide swath of 7 to 11 inches of snowfall fell along an axis from near Hudson in northeastern Stafford County, to north of Haviland in Kiowa County, through northern parts of both Ford and Gray Counties, to just north of Big Bow in extreme northeastern Stanton County.  On either side of this heavy band of snow, an area of 4 to 6 inches of snow fell, basically south of a line from Shallow Water in southeast Scott County to Brownell in northeast Ness County to Pfeifer in southeast Ellis County, as well as north of a line from Elkhart in southeast Morton County to near Ashland in Clark county to near Sawyer in southeastern Pratt County.  In northern parts of DDC���s CWA, as well as in southeastern parts, 2 to 4 inches of snow fell.  The highest snowfall report received from this event was 11 inches at Ingalls in Gray County, with drifts as high as 5 feet in the Dodge City area also reported.  Winds during the event were from the north to northwest at 20 to 35 mph, which caused many areas of deep drifting and widespread travel problems.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 6 inches was reported in Spearville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front crossed the region on New Year���s Day. A broad area of lake effect snows develop along the south shores of Lakes Erie and Ontario late on the first. Some narrow intense bands developed in this area and extended up to twenty miles inland. The activity continued through Saturday (3rd) and then strengthened in place Saturday Night as a large area of moisture spiraled around a massive coastal storm off New England.  A general burst of moderate to heavy snow accompanied this synoptic feature as it dropped south and southwest across the entire region during Sunday, then finally the lake effect weakened and retreated to near the lakes again Sunday night.  This event was unique in many ways, most notably in the large amounts of snow off Lake Ontario back across much of the Niagara frontier. A general one to two feet fell over two days, with up to 30 inches around Niagara Falls. Another area of very heavy snow focused on Wayne to Oswego County where two to three feet fell. The Rochester area caught a bit less, but still up to 18 inches near the Lake.  Off Lake Erie, two feet or more fell near Chautauqua Lake from Mayville to Jamestown. |Specific snowfall totals Off Lake Erie included:  Mayville 31���; Jamestown 28���; and Perrysburg 26���. Abundant rain advanced north into the region in advance of an area of low pressure to the west while a frontal boundary remained draped over the region. An average of 2 to 5 inches of rain fell from this system onto an already saturated ground from recent snow melt and rainfall. The heavy rain contributed to widespread flash flooding, mudslides, areal flooding, and river flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure center moved eastward across central Illinois and Indiana, dragging a cold front southeast across the Lower Ohio Valley. Gusty winds and bitterly cold arctic air arrived in the wake of the cold front. Wind chills fell to as low as minus 10 north and west of Carbondale.

Between the 19th and 21st, a storm system stalled over the Mid-Mississippi River Valley before pushing east on the 22nd. Numerous showers and even a few thunderstorms helped to produce average rain amounts around one inch. A few locations received up to two inches. This rainfall pushed the Green River above flood stage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Minor flooding occurred on the Green River. At the river gage at Paradise, the river crested at 383.07 feet on the 25th. Flood stage there is 380 feet. Minor flooding of low-lying woods and fields occurred near the river.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Gusty south winds near White Bird caused damage to a Hamburger Stand Trailer.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fairly warm and moist system brought accumulating snow to the higher terrain and rain mixed with freezing rain to the lower valleys of western Montana. Total snow amounts ranged between 7 to 12 inches.  This system carried over from December 31st, 2009.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Montana DOT reported 8 to 12 inches of new snow over Marias Pass.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The first significant snow storm of the 2010-11 winter season dumped between 2 and 12 inches of snow on eastern Kentucky on December 12th and 13th. The highest snowfall totals occurred in Bell, Lee, and Leslie, and McCreary counties where 10-12 inches were reported. There were several culprits for this snow event, as areas of low pressure moving across the lower Great Lakes and up the eastern slopes of the Appalachian Mountains combined forces over the Ohio and Tennessee valleys. The highest snowfall totals occurred along the Kentucky River basin as an intense band of moderate to heavy snowfall remained in place there during the overnight hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Eight tenths of an inch of snow fell near Prestonsburg between 9 pm and midnight.

Lesser amounts of snow fell to the north and south of this line, but some areas did pick up a little light freezing drizzle.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very large upper low moved off the Pacific and across the Rockies. Ahead of this system southwesterly flow brought significant moisture into the region. As the storm system and associated cold front moved slowly through southern New Mexico, snow levels dropped to around 5000 feet with almost 2 feet of snow reported near Cloudcroft.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totals across the Sacramento Mountains were 22.9 inches 1.8 miles southwest of Cloudcroft, 18.5 inches 5 miles northeast of Cloudcroft, and 6.5 inches 1 mile west of High Rolls at elevation 6601 feet.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Highest snowfall reported in zone was 9.9 inches 6.1 miles north of Silver City. Other reports included 9.0 inches 3.4 miles north of Silver City, 6.0 inches 3.5 south of Silver City and 5.5 inches 8.9 miles east-northeast of Bayard.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cutoff low moved out of Arizona and across New Mexico with plenty of moisture in place from previous storm systems. Snow levels started out around 8000 feet and quickly fell behind strong cold front to below 5000 feet. Snowfall of up to 11 inches was reported in Cloudcroft.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall reports across the zone included 9.0 inches 10 miles north of Central at the Signal Peak SNOTEL, 7.0 inches 10 miles northwest of Kingston at the McKnight Cabin SNOTEL, and 6.0 inches 9 miles east-northeast of Bayard from a CoCoRaHs observer.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The first significant snow storm of the 2010-11 winter season dumped between 2 and 12 inches of snow on eastern Kentucky on December 12th and 13th. The highest snowfall totals occurred in Bell, Lee, and Leslie, and McCreary counties where 10-12 inches were reported. There were several culprits for this snow event, as areas of low pressure moving across the lower Great Lakes and up the eastern slopes of the Appalachian Mountains combined forces over the Ohio and Tennessee valleys. The highest snowfall totals occurred along the Kentucky River basin as an intense band of moderate to heavy snowfall remained in place there during the overnight hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Magoffin county Rescue Squad reported that 5 inches of snow had fallen 5 miles east of Salyersville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Freezing rain produced ice accumulations of a quarter inch or a little more in extreme northeast Nebraska.Travel and walking were made extremely hazardous, and power lines and trees were damaged.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Freezing rain produced ice accumulations of around a quarter inch. Travel and walking were made extremely hazardous and difficult. Damage to trees and power lines was reported, and there were scattered power outages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Northwest winds gusting over 45 mph, along with existing loose snow cover, caused blowing snow, which reduced visibilities to a quarter mile or less in some areas. Travel was difficult to impossible because of the low visibilities and drifting snow. Some schools, businesses, and roads closed.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Northwest winds gusting to over 45 mph combined with existing snow cover to cause blowing snow. there were a few areas where visibility dropped to a quarter mile or less. Some businesses, schools, and roads were closed because of the low visibilities and the drifting snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system moved from northern Old Mexico into New Mexico Wednesday night, January 27th, 2010.  This winter system then plowed east-northeast through Kansas, Texas and Oklahoma Thursday and early Friday, January 28th and 29th.  This brought significant snowfall to much of southwest and south central Kansas.  The precipitation began as light snow late Wednesday night, then picked up and continued as heavy snow for much of Thursday and Thursday night.  While snow persisted Friday morning, January 29th, in parts of our southeastern CWA, not much additional accumulation occurred.  Reports received Friday morning, January 29th, revealed a 5 to 20 mile wide swath of 7 to 11 inches of snowfall fell along an axis from near Hudson in northeastern Stafford County, to north of Haviland in Kiowa County, through northern parts of both Ford and Gray Counties, to just north of Big Bow in extreme northeastern Stanton County.  On either side of this heavy band of snow, an area of 4 to 6 inches of snow fell, basically south of a line from Shallow Water in southeast Scott County to Brownell in northeast Ness County to Pfeifer in southeast Ellis County, as well as north of a line from Elkhart in southeast Morton County to near Ashland in Clark county to near Sawyer in southeastern Pratt County.  In northern parts of DDC���s CWA, as well as in southeastern parts, 2 to 4 inches of snow fell.  The highest snowfall report received from this event was 11 inches at Ingalls in Gray County, with drifts as high as 5 feet in the Dodge City area also reported.  Winds during the event were from the north to northwest at 20 to 35 mph, which caused many areas of deep drifting and widespread travel problems.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 6 inches was reported in Syracuse.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Daytime air temperatures reached between 98 and 106 while heat indices reached the 110 to 115 degree range. Nighttime temperatures only fell into the 75 to 80 degree range through this period which was separated from the first episode by a brief 48 hour period.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold high pressure settled across Deep South Texas on the evening of January 9th, continuing through the early morning of January 10th.  Clear skies and light winds allowed temperatures to fall rapidly back into the 30s after sunset. After midnight, sheltered or wind protected locations plummeted into the upper teens to lower 20s - another hard freeze - while locations with a continuing 4 to 8 mph northerly wind fell to or just below freezing for several hours. Higher relatively humidity allowed widespread frost to form, thickest in hollows and other low lying areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Clear, generally calm conditions allowed temperatures to fall rapidly after sunset on the 9th, with readings reaching the freezing point shortly after midnight on the 10th and continuing for an hour after daybreak on the 10th.  Low temperatures early on the 10th range from the lower and mid 20s well west of Highway 77 toward Hidalgo County, to around 30 just east of Highway 77.  Raymondville fell to 29 degrees; freezing temperatures lasted generally from 4 to 8 hours, with a local hard freeze, or temperatures below 28, estimated to last from 2 to 4 hours across the western portion of the county.||While additional minor damage to dryland crops and tender vegetation was likely, the overall impact of the freeze for Willacy County was that of a bullet dodged since temperatures between each cold night rebounded into the upper 40s and lower 50s during the afternoon of the 9th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Abundant rain advanced north into the region in advance of an area of low pressure to the west while a frontal boundary remained draped over the region. An average of 2 to 5 inches of rain fell from this system onto an already saturated ground from recent snow melt and rainfall. The heavy rain contributed to widespread flash flooding, mudslides, areal flooding, and river flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain prompted flash flooding of small streams and creeks in and around Francisco. Damage values are estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On December 24th, Christmas Eve, a low pressure system traversed along the Gulf Of Mexico. Moisture streamed up into the area but the Jackson CWA was spared  the heavier snowfall as that occurred further east. The event was worthy of Winter Weather Advisories with a Winter Storm Warning issued for the higher elevations in Harlan and Letcher counties. A powerful east coast low pressure developed and traveled up the east coast. The fully developed low pressure system brought northerly flow into eastern Kentucky and created an extended upslope event. The event prompted the continuance of the advisories and winter storm warnings into December 27th till noon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tenth of an inch of snow fell in West Liberty. The snow was covering the roads and was coming down heavily.

A long lasting lake effect snow event affected much of the south shore of Lake Superior, with a general 6 to 12 inches of total snowfall. Localized amounts of up to 19 inches fell in Gile, with 14.5 inches falling in Oulu.

Record Snowfall occurred across the greater Burlington area on January 2nd into January 3rd.||A powerful ocean storm southeast of Nova Scotia during the late afternoon of January 2nd, retrograded into the Gulf of Maine near Rockport, Maine by the morning of January 3rd and then proceeded to return to the Atlantic Ocean during the afternoon of January 3rd.||Wraparound snows moved into northern Vermont during the afternoon and evening hours of January 2nd and continued through the afternoon of January 3rd. The windward side (west) of the various mountain ranges in Vermont witnessed the heaviest snowfall due to upslope conditions with the leeward side (east) received less snow due to downslope. In addition, some training of mesoscale snow bands, likely a result of upslope and convergence within the Champlain Valley of Vermont accounted for record snowfall in the Burlington area. ||Favorable upslope regions received 8 to 18 inches of snowfall with over 30 inches in the greater Burlington area. Meanwhile downslope regions received 2 to 6 inches of snowfall. In addition, brisk northwest winds of 15 to 25 mph with higher gusts caused considerable blowing and drfiting of the snow with 4 to 5 foot snow drifts reported.||A record 33.1 inches of snow fell with this storm at Burlington Int'l Airport in South Burlington, which surpassed the old record of 29.8 inches that occurred on December 25-28 in 1969. ||Some other specific snowfall totals; 30 inches in Essex Junction and Colchester (Chittenden county), 25 inches in Monkton (Addison county) and Milton (Chittenden county), 24 inches in Charlotte (Chittenden county), 22 inches in Jeffersonville (Lamoille county), Underhill and Jericho (Chittenden county), 18 inches in Canaan (Essex county) and Sheldon Springs (Franklin county), 16 inches in Cambridge (Lamoille county), 14 inches in Barton (Orleans county), Danby (Rutland county) and Lincoln (Addison county).

As one winter storm event ended, hardly 14 hours passed and portions of the region were back in a second winter storm. These rare back-to-back storms ended up shutting down a good majority of events across the area. A second strong surface low pressure system lifted out of southwest Minnesota and tracked toward the Minnesota arrowhead, producing another swath of 6 to 8 inches of snow along with very gusty north winds. This resulted in winter storm conditions from New Years Eve into the 2011 New Year.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust to 70 mph was reported at Browning 6WNW. Also, a gust to 72 mph was reported at Heart Butte.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a strong upper low moved across the area, flurries and bands of light snowfall developed during the early morning hours on December 26th, affecting much of Central Alabama through the day. Flurries as far south as Troy, one inch accumulations across northwest Central Alabama, and a dusting at many locations in between were reported. Gusty northwesterly winds combined with the light snowfall to bring visibilities down to around one mile at times. ||Roadways were slick from the Christmas Day snowfall. As the additional light snowfall combined with temperatures near or below freezing, travel conditions remained hazardous. Travel was discouraged across much of the area. With below freezing temperatures, snow remained on the ground for several days in parts of north Central Alabama.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Light snowfall resulted in a dusting and reduced visibilities at times.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moist northwest flow off Lake Michigan combined with terrain effects brought yet another round of light snow to eastern Kentucky on January 5th. The highest snowfall amount recorded occurred in Letcher county. Two to three inches of snow fell in a 24 hour period, with isolated accumulations of 4-5 inches across the higher terrain. All in all 1-3 inches of snow fell in the affected counties from late in the day on January 4th through late in the morning on the 5th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A member of the public observed 3.5 inches of snow on Little Black Mountain since yesterday.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The first significant snow storm of the 2010-11 winter season dumped between 2 and 12 inches of snow on eastern Kentucky on December 12th and 13th. The highest snowfall totals occurred in Bell, Lee, and Leslie, and McCreary counties where 10-12 inches were reported. There were several culprits for this snow event, as areas of low pressure moving across the lower Great Lakes and up the eastern slopes of the Appalachian Mountains combined forces over the Ohio and Tennessee valleys. The highest snowfall totals occurred along the Kentucky River basin as an intense band of moderate to heavy snowfall remained in place there during the overnight hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Seven inches of snow was measured in Beattyville.

The snow began during the midmorning hours on January 7th and lasted until 7 or 8z on January 8th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: One inch of snow fell near Moon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system moved from northern Old Mexico into New Mexico Wednesday night, January 27th, 2010.  This winter system then plowed east-northeast through Kansas, Texas and Oklahoma Thursday and early Friday, January 28th and 29th.  This brought significant snowfall to much of southwest and south central Kansas.  The precipitation began as light snow late Wednesday night, then picked up and continued as heavy snow for much of Thursday and Thursday night.  While snow persisted Friday morning, January 29th, in parts of our southeastern CWA, not much additional accumulation occurred.  Reports received Friday morning, January 29th, revealed a 5 to 20 mile wide swath of 7 to 11 inches of snowfall fell along an axis from near Hudson in northeastern Stafford County, to north of Haviland in Kiowa County, through northern parts of both Ford and Gray Counties, to just north of Big Bow in extreme northeastern Stanton County.  On either side of this heavy band of snow, an area of 4 to 6 inches of snow fell, basically south of a line from Shallow Water in southeast Scott County to Brownell in northeast Ness County to Pfeifer in southeast Ellis County, as well as north of a line from Elkhart in southeast Morton County to near Ashland in Clark county to near Sawyer in southeastern Pratt County.  In northern parts of DDC���s CWA, as well as in southeastern parts, 2 to 4 inches of snow fell.  The highest snowfall report received from this event was 11 inches at Ingalls in Gray County, with drifts as high as 5 feet in the Dodge City area also reported.  Winds during the event were from the north to northwest at 20 to 35 mph, which caused many areas of deep drifting and widespread travel problems.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 6 inches was reported in Scott City.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold high pressure settled across Deep South Texas on the evening of January 9th, continuing through the early morning of January 10th.  Clear skies and light winds allowed temperatures to fall rapidly back into the 30s after sunset. After midnight, sheltered or wind protected locations plummeted into the upper teens to lower 20s - another hard freeze - while locations with a continuing 4 to 8 mph northerly wind fell to or just below freezing for several hours. Higher relatively humidity allowed widespread frost to form, thickest in hollows and other low lying areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Clear, calm conditions allowed temperatures to plummet after sunset on the 9th across the hunting grounds and King Ranch of Brooks County, reaching the freezing point by late evening on its way down to near 20 in rural pockets, and upper 20s elsewhere, by daybreak on the 10th.  Temperatures touched 20 at the Falfurrias cooperative site at the Hollywood Hunting Camp, but only fell to 28 at the Brooks County airport, exposed to more wind. Freezing temperatures lasted up to 9 and one half hours, with a hard freeze, or temperatures below 28 degrees, lasting between 3 and 6 hours in locations away from the city of Falfurrias.||Damage to newly planted coastal grasses was noted by the Farm Services Agency of Brooks and Jim Hogg County in eastern Brooks County from the freezing conditions between the 8th and 10th.  Dollar values were not available as of this writing.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold high pressure settled across Deep South Texas on the evening of January 9th, continuing through the early morning of January 10th.  Clear skies and light winds allowed temperatures to fall rapidly back into the 30s after sunset. After midnight, sheltered or wind protected locations plummeted into the upper teens to lower 20s - another hard freeze - while locations with a continuing 4 to 8 mph northerly wind fell to or just below freezing for several hours. Higher relatively humidity allowed widespread frost to form, thickest in hollows and other low lying areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Clear, generally calm conditions allowed temperatures to fall rapidly after sunset on the 9th. Near the coast, a light breeze from the Gulf arrived overnight, increasing humidity and holding temperatures from dropping much lower than the freezing point.  Along the coast, temperatures did not reach 32; however, locations within 5 miles of the coast likely fell below 32 for 2 to 4 hours.  This included Laguna Atascosa National Wildlife Refuge, which dropped to 31 after 2 AM and remained between 31 and 33 degrees until after sunrise.  The Cameron County Airport near Bayview dropped to 30 and also held near 32 or just above for much of the night.||No additional significant damage was likely with this freeze.

Lesser amounts of snow fell to the north and south of this line, but some areas did pick up a little light freezing drizzle.

A strong cold front crossed the region on New Year���s Day. A broad area of lake effect snows develop along the south shores of Lakes Erie and Ontario late on the first. Some narrow intense bands developed in this area and extended up to twenty miles inland. The activity continued through Saturday (3rd) and then strengthened in place Saturday Night as a large area of moisture spiraled around a massive coastal storm off New England.  A general burst of moderate to heavy snow accompanied this synoptic feature as it dropped south and southwest across the entire region during Sunday, then finally the lake effect weakened and retreated to near the lakes again Sunday night.  This event was unique in many ways, most notably in the large amounts of snow off Lake Ontario back across much of the Niagara frontier. A general one to two feet fell over two days, with up to 30 inches around Niagara Falls. Another area of very heavy snow focused on Wayne to Oswego County where two to three feet fell. The Rochester area caught a bit less, but still up to 18 inches near the Lake.  Off Lake Erie, two feet or more fell near Chautauqua Lake from Mayville to Jamestown. |Specific snowfall totals Off Lake Erie included:  Mayville 31���; Jamestown 28���; and Perrysburg 26���. Off Lake Ontario, the reports included: 42��� at Fulton; 38��� at Lacona; 36��� at Marion; 34��� at Scriba; 32��� at Hannibal; 31��� at Niagara Falls; 30��� at Pulaski; 26��� at North Tonawanda, Kent and Williamson; 24��� at Lockport; 22��� at Oswego; 19��� at North Amherst; 16��� at Perry; 14��� at Tonawanda; and 9��� to 18��� in Rochester (from north to south across the city).

Abundant rain advanced north into the region in advance of an area of low pressure to the west while a frontal boundary remained draped over the region. An average of 2 to 5 inches of rain fell from this system onto an already saturated ground from recent snow melt and rainfall. The heavy rain contributed to widespread flash flooding, mudslides, areal flooding, and river flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: After approximately four inches of rain fell over Patrick County, flash flooding occurred. Pole Bridge Creek and most other small streams and creek in the eastern part of the county were out of their banks. Damage values are estimated.

A couple of rounds of thunderstorms developed over western Texas and moved northeast into northern Texas, as a strong storm system approached from the southwestern United States. The thunderstorms developed ahead of a dry line that was located east of Lubbock. These thunderstorms remained below severe levels before intensifying over parts of Oklahoma. Later in the evening, another area of strong to occasionally severe thunderstorms moved out of west Texas. These thunderstorms also moved northeast, and produced hail up to quarter size in Wilbarger and Wichita counties. No damage was reported with the hail.

A mid level circulation moved from western North Dakota into eastern South Dakota. The reflection at the surface was an inverted trough, which mainly set up over the central Dakotas. Heavy snow fell near the inverted trough, which did make it into portions of west central Minnesota. A band of 4 to 6 inches of snow fell across portions of Wilkin County along with blowing snow and cold wind chills.

An arctic front swept southward across the west Texas region during the evening hours of the 6th.  The frontal passage was accompanied by northerly winds sustained above 30 mph with a few gusts near 50 mph. The winds damaged transmission lines south of Childress, and resulted in a short-lived power outage.
Gusty winds affected the immediate lee of the Sierra for wind-prone locations and the higher elevations around the Reno, Carson City, and Minden area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On December 24th, Christmas Eve, a low pressure system traversed along the Gulf Of Mexico. Moisture streamed up into the area but the Jackson CWA was spared  the heavier snowfall as that occurred further east. The event was worthy of Winter Weather Advisories with a Winter Storm Warning issued for the higher elevations in Harlan and Letcher counties. A powerful east coast low pressure developed and traveled up the east coast. The fully developed low pressure system brought northerly flow into eastern Kentucky and created an extended upslope event. The event prompted the continuance of the advisories and winter storm warnings into December 27th till noon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: N4UTG reported that 9 inches of snow had fallen in Ermine since Friday evening.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of surface low pressure formed over south central North Dakota on the evening of the 20th and tracked into central Minnesota by mid morning of the 21st. This helped spread a swath of 6 to 8 inches of snow from Devils Lake to Reynolds (North Dakota) to Mahnomen (Minnesota). Lesser amounts of snow fell to the north and south of this line, but some areas did pick up a little light freezing drizzle.

A strong cold front crossed the region on New Year���s Day. A broad area of lake effect snows develop along the south shores of Lakes Erie and Ontario late on the first. Some narrow intense bands developed in this area and extended up to twenty miles inland. The activity continued through Saturday (3rd) and then strengthened in place Saturday Night as a large area of moisture spiraled around a massive coastal storm off New England.  A general burst of moderate to heavy snow accompanied this synoptic feature as it dropped south and southwest across the entire region during Sunday, then finally the lake effect weakened and retreated to near the lakes again Sunday night.  This event was unique in many ways, most notably in the large amounts of snow off Lake Ontario back across much of the Niagara frontier. A general one to two feet fell over two days, with up to 30 inches around Niagara Falls. Another area of very heavy snow focused on Wayne to Oswego County where two to three feet fell. The Rochester area caught a bit less, but still up to 18 inches near the Lake. Abundant rain advanced north into the region in advance of an area of low pressure to the west while a frontal boundary remained draped over the region. An average of 2 to 5 inches of rain fell from this system onto an already saturated ground from recent snow melt and rainfall. The heavy rain contributed to widespread flash flooding, mudslides, areal flooding, and river flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain prompted flash flooding along 19th Street.  The water depth was 6 to 12 inches. Damage values are estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A wet Pacific storm system produced isolated thunderstorms across south central Arizona during the evening hours on December 22nd. Some of these storms generated gusty and damaging winds, in addition to locally heavy rainfall.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Gusty thunderstorm winds, estimated to be 50 knots, blew down a 12 inch diameter tree in north central Phoenix. Other small tree limbs were blown down, and some shingles were blown off of a roof.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system produced rain changing to snow during the early morning hours of February 12th. Two to three inches accumulated over portions of Madison and Houston Counties, with a maximum of 3.5 inches over northern Houston County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A widespread 2 to 3 inches of snow fell over Houston County. Reports included 3.5 inches near Weches, 2.5 inches near Latexo, and 2 inches near Crockett, Lovelady, Kennard and Grapeland.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall reports ranged from 3 to 5 inches across the county with highest totals over northern sections. Crockett measured 3 inches of snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moist northwest flow off Lake Michigan combined with terrain effects brought yet another round of light snow to eastern Kentucky on January 5th. The highest snowfall amount recorded occurred in Letcher county. Two to three inches of snow fell in a 24 hour period, with isolated accumulations of 4-5 inches across the higher terrain. All in all 1-3 inches of snow fell in the affected counties from late in the day on January 4th through late in the morning on the 5th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter reported 1/2 inch of new snowfall, and a total snow depth of 3.5 inches in Isom. The total snowfall measurement included snow that fell on January 4th as well.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Persistent northwest flow off Lake Michigan led to one more round of upslope snowfall for Letcher and Martin counties on January 5th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter reported that 5.5 inches of snow had fallen in Thornton since snow began there on the morning of January 4th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and then through the mid Atlantic region on January 29th and 30th. The snow first began falling across eastern Kentucky during the late afternoon and evening hours of January 29th as the storm moved across central Tennessee. The snow finally came to an end late in the day on January 30th as the area of low pressure moved up the east coast. Snowfall amounts of 4-8 inches were quite common around the area, with accumulations as high as 11 inches reported on Black Mountain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Highway Dept reported that 5 inches of snow had fallen across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On December 24th, Christmas Eve, a low pressure system traversed along the Gulf Of Mexico. Moisture streamed up into the area but the Jackson CWA was spared  the heavier snowfall as that occurred further east. The event was worthy of Winter Weather Advisories with a Winter Storm Warning issued for the higher elevations in Harlan and Letcher counties. A powerful east coast low pressure developed and traveled up the east coast. The fully developed low pressure system brought northerly flow into eastern Kentucky and created an extended upslope event. The event prompted the continuance of the advisories and winter storm warnings into December 27th till noon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An inch and a  half of snow fell 2 miles north northwest of Dice.

The snow began during the midmorning hours on January 7th and lasted until 7 or 8z on January 8th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six tenths of an inch of new snow fell 2 miles east southeast of Talbert with 1 inch of snow on the ground.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold high pressure settled across Deep South Texas on the evening of January 9th, continuing through the early morning of January 10th.  Clear skies and light winds allowed temperatures to fall rapidly back into the 30s after sunset. After midnight, sheltered or wind protected locations plummeted into the upper teens to lower 20s - another hard freeze - while locations with a continuing 4 to 8 mph northerly wind fell to or just below freezing for several hours. Higher relatively humidity allowed widespread frost to form, thickest in hollows and other low lying areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Clear, calm conditions allowed temperatures to plummet after sunset on the 9th across the King Ranch, reaching the freezing point toward midnight, and bottoming out between 25 and 30 in most areas by daybreak on the 10th.  Temperatures touched 26 at Armstrong, and 30 degrees a bit east of Sarita.  While freezing temperatures lasted an estimated 8 hours or so, an overnight light wind from the Gulf kept a widespread hard freeze from developing.  Estimates from the cooperative sites suggest 2 to 4 hours of hard freeze, or temperatures below 28 degrees, during the pre dawn hours of the 10th.||Information on any grazing land damage was not known as of this writing.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front moved across the San Francisco and Monterey Bay area causing isolated strong winds, snow flurries at higher elevations and additional rain. Since the ground was saturated from the early week's storms many of the previously flooded areas remained closed.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong wind caused several large trees to fall into the roadway along State route 84 near Woodside. A half-mile stretch of the highway was closed for part of the day to remove the trees.

A strong storm system tracking northeast from the Gulf of Mexico spread heavy snow and freezing rain into Central North Carolina the evening of January 29th. The snow continued into the morning hours of January 30th. Between 5 to 10 inches of snow blanketed areas along and north of Highway 64 with up to a foot of snow reported along the Virginia border. Locations across the southern piedmont, southern coastal plain and sandhills experienced a mix of snow and freezing rain. Freezing rain accumulations ranged from one-eighth to a half inch of ice.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 3 to 4 inches of snow fell across the county.  A few vehicle accidents and some power outages were reported. Due to the cold temperatures icy road conditions persisted for several days resulting in the closure of schools and businesses.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Alberta clipper tracked southeast through the Ohio Valley on Thursday, January 7th. Very cold air was in place, which allowed for a very fluffy snow to accumulate over a prolonged period of time. Snow totals from this event ranged from two to five inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A spotter measured 4 inches of snow in Covington, while another measured the same in Troy.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong storm center developed just off the Queen Charlotte Islands on the afternoon of 10/9. The center recurved to the NW over the Panhandle causing hurricane force winds, with many, many power outages and downed trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Although there were no land observations available for this wind storm, hurricane force NE wind was detected at Cape Spenser at 1400 AKST on 10/9.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Light to moderate snow fell across the region February 9th into early February 10th as an intensifying area of low pressure tracked northeastward from the Tennessee Valley into northern Ohio. Snowfall totals generally ranged between 6 and 10 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A steady light to moderate snow fell February 9th into early February 10th with snowfall totals ranging between 6 and 9 inches across the county.  The South Bend Airport reported 6.5 inches of total snow accumulation.  Winds of 15 to 25 mph allowed for some blowing and drifting of the snow.  The accumulating snow and wind led to slide-offs and accidents, with many schools closing across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strengthening area of low pressure tracked through central Indiana and northern Ohio, bringing a period of wet heavy snow to much of southern Lower Michigan late on February 21st into early February 22nd.  Snowfall amounts of 5-8 were common across the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy wet snow developed during the evening hours of February 21st and continued into the morning hours of February 22nd.  The snow was heavy at times, with total snow accumulations across the county generally ranging between 4 and 7 inches as temperatures hovered near freezing.  There were reports of slide-offs and accidents across the county, including school delays and closings.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system moved from northern Old Mexico into New Mexico Wednesday night, January 27th, 2010.  This winter system then plowed east-northeast through Kansas, Texas and Oklahoma Thursday and early Friday, January 28th and 29th.  This brought significant snowfall to much of southwest and south central Kansas.  The precipitation began as light snow late Wednesday night, then picked up and continued as heavy snow for much of Thursday and Thursday night.  While snow persisted Friday morning, January 29th, in parts of our southeastern CWA, not much additional accumulation occurred.  Reports received Friday morning, January 29th, revealed a 5 to 20 mile wide swath of 7 to 11 inches of snowfall fell along an axis from near Hudson in northeastern Stafford County, to north of Haviland in Kiowa County, through northern parts of both Ford and Gray Counties, to just north of Big Bow in extreme northeastern Stanton County.  On either side of this heavy band of snow, an area of 4 to 6 inches of snow fell, basically south of a line from Shallow Water in southeast Scott County to Brownell in northeast Ness County to Pfeifer in southeast Ellis County, as well as north of a line from Elkhart in southeast Morton County to near Ashland in Clark county to near Sawyer in southeastern Pratt County.  In northern parts of DDC���s CWA, as well as in southeastern parts, 2 to 4 inches of snow fell.  The highest snowfall report received from this event was 11 inches at Ingalls in Gray County, with drifts as high as 5 feet in the Dodge City area also reported.  Winds during the event were from the north to northwest at 20 to 35 mph, which caused many areas of deep drifting and widespread travel problems.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 6 inches was reported at a location 6 miles west of Cimarron.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Abundant rain advanced north into the region in advance of an area of low pressure to the west while a frontal boundary remained draped over the region. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large and very moist Pacific storm system brought widespread heavy precipitation to Utah over a five day period. EVENT_NARRATIVE: Penny size hail fell along Highway 67 near the Lawrence and Randolph County line.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The first significant snow storm of the 2010-11 winter season dumped between 2 and 12 inches of snow on eastern Kentucky on December 12th and 13th. The highest snowfall totals occurred in Bell, Lee, and Leslie, and McCreary counties where 10-12 inches were reported. There were several culprits for this snow event, as areas of low pressure moving across the lower Great Lakes and up the eastern slopes of the Appalachian Mountains combined forces over the Ohio and Tennessee valleys. The highest snowfall totals occurred along the Kentucky River basin as an intense band of moderate to heavy snowfall remained in place there during the overnight hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The 12 hour snowfall total at Buckhorn was 6 inches as of 630 am.

Drier than normal conditions which began in the summer continued through the fall and into December.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rainfall totals continued to be below normal over most of South Florida in December, with most areas receiving only 25 to 50 percent of normal for the month. As a result, severe drought conditions (D2) developed over Hendry and western Palm Beach counties by the second week of December. Rainfall totals since June 1 were about 5 to 10 inches below normal in Hendry County as well as western sections of Palm Beach County. Most wells across the area were running at about 10 percent of normal water levels. The level of Lake Okeechobee dropped to 12.4 feet by the end of December, which is 2.2 feet below normal. The Keetch-Byram Drought Index (KBDI) was in the 550 to 600 range, which reflects a high fire danger and very low soil moisture values.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A series of storms struck northern California during this week...leading to prolonged snowstorms.   Initially the snow level was in the 4500-5000 foot range...but it dropped to near 3500 feet in the middle of the week.   During this particular event...the snow level started off high and dropped to the 3500-4000 foot range toward the end of the event.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow levels remained above the populated areas at 4500-5000 feet.  However, RAWS stations in the area reported significant precipitation.  The RAWS at Scott Mountain near Callahan at 5900 feet recorded 1.08 inches liquid equivalent in 11 hours between 17/1000 and 17/2100 PST.  Converting this to snow, even using a very wet 6 inches snow to 1 inch rain ratio, yields enough snow to verify the warning.

Combs bridge.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On December 24th, Christmas Eve, a low pressure system traversed along the Gulf Of Mexico. The event was worthy of Winter Weather Advisories with a Winter Storm Warning issued for the higher elevations in Harlan and Letcher counties. A powerful east coast low pressure developed and traveled up the east coast. The fully developed low pressure system brought northerly flow into eastern Kentucky and created an extended upslope event. The event prompted the continuance of the advisories and winter storm warnings into December 27th till noon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system moved from northern Old Mexico into New Mexico Wednesday night, January 27th, 2010.  This winter system then plowed east-northeast through Kansas, Texas and Oklahoma Thursday and early Friday, January 28th and 29th.  This brought significant snowfall to much of southwest and south central Kansas.  The precipitation began as light snow late Wednesday night, then picked up and continued as heavy snow for much of Thursday and Thursday night.  While snow persisted Friday morning, January 29th, in parts of our southeastern CWA, not much additional accumulation occurred.  Reports received Friday morning, January 29th, revealed a 5 to 20 mile wide swath of 7 to 11 inches of snowfall fell along an axis from near Hudson in northeastern Stafford County, to north of Haviland in Kiowa County, through northern parts of both Ford and Gray Counties, to just north of Big Bow in extreme northeastern Stanton County.  On either side of this heavy band of snow, an area of 4 to 6 inches of snow fell, basically south of a line from Shallow Water in southeast Scott County to Brownell in northeast Ness County to Pfeifer in southeast Ellis County, as well as north of a line from Elkhart in southeast Morton County to near Ashland in Clark county to near Sawyer in southeastern Pratt County.  In northern parts of DDC���s CWA, as well as in southeastern parts, 2 to 4 inches of snow fell.  The highest snowfall report received from this event was 11 inches at Ingalls in Gray County, with drifts as high as 5 feet in the Dodge City area also reported.  Winds during the event were from the north to northwest at 20 to 35 mph, which caused many areas of deep drifting and widespread travel problems.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 7 inches was reported in St. John.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure tracking from the Plains northeastward into the Great Lakes brought a period of moderate to heavy snow to parts of central Illinois from the evening of January 6th through the morning of January 7th.  Snowfall was greatest along and north of I-72...where 5 to 7 inch totals were common.  Once the snow subsided, gusty northwesterly winds created considerable blowing and drifting across the area through the night of January 7th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous weather observers across Tazewell County measured around 6 inches of snow.

CZ_NAME: DIXON ENTRANCE TO CAPE DECISION COASTAL AREA
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very strong hurricane force low developed south of Kodiak Island on the morning of 10/31. As the storm center moved ENE, a strong front moved into the Queen Charlotte Islands with the very strong surface pressure gradient just brushing the west coast of Prince of Wales Island. Wind to 72 MPH was observed with this system.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hydaburg AWOS had a measured gust to 60 KT at 2016 AKST on 10/31. Numerous gusts in the 50s were observed that evening.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moderate strength front stalled just off the coast on the evening of 10/28. Moist air was forced up Lynn Canal which caused heavy snow overnight in White Pass. 6 to 8 inches of new snow fell there in 12 hours on that night into the early morning of 10/29.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Along the Klondike Highway up to White Pass, 6 to 8 inches of new snow fell between the hours of 2100 AKST 10/28 and 0700 10/29. Alaska DOT also reported winds to 30 MPH with very poor visibility.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very warm and unstable air mass developed across the region on January 20th.  This air mass was accompanied by unusually high dewpoint values for late January with ambient temperatures approaching the 70 degree mark.  A very strong and vigorous storm system moved out of the Great Basin and into the Southern Plains and Lower Mississippi Valley during the late afternoon and evening hours of January 20th.  Wind shear throughout the atmosphere was very strong and supportive of strong to severe thunderstorms.  Low level wind shear was significant enough such that super cell thunderstorms developed across the region, producing tornadoes, large hail and damaging wind gusts.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding washed out portions of Highway 317 through Rainbow Canyon, as well as Kane Springs Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A series of storms fueled by a tropical moisture tap pounded the Mojave Desert and southern Great Basin for several days.  Extremely heavy snow and widespread flooding resulted.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Mojave River overflowed its banks due to a combination of heavy rain and emergency release of water from Cedar Spring Dam near Arrowhead. Numerous roads were covered with mud and closed, one bridge was washed out, a broken levee flooded a neighborhood, and three swift water rescues were performed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A series of storms fueled by a tropical moisture tap pounded the Mojave Desert and southern Great Basin for several days.  Extremely heavy snow and widespread flooding resulted.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Pahranagat Wash and Muddy River both flooded. Warm Springs Road near Moapa was flooded 2-3 feet deep, a foot of water flowed through the intersection of Gubler and Heyer streets in Logandale, Northshore Drive was flooded west of Overton Beach, water 6 feet deep flowed across Cooper Street in Overton, and the Muddy River crested 7.3 feet above flood stage in Glendale.  Cooper Street was closed until December 28th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and then through the mid Atlantic region on January 29th and 30th. The snow first began falling across eastern Kentucky during the late afternoon and evening hours of January 29th as the storm moved across central Tennessee. The snow finally came to an end late in the day on January 30th as the area of low pressure moved up the east coast. Snowfall amounts of 4-8 inches were quite common around the area, with accumulations as high as 11 inches reported on Black Mountain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six inches of snowfall was measured in Middlesboro by a member of the public.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fast moving storm system tracked southeast across the Central Plains producing a swath of 3 to 6 inches of snow along with strong northwest winds.  The very dry nature of the snow combined with strong northwest winds to produce near zero visibilities on area roadways during the evening hours of January 6th.  The area already had a powdery snowpack of 6 to 12 inches which also served to enhance the blowing and drifting of snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Observer estimates 5.1 inches of new snow since around noon.  Strong northwest winds are now producing blowing and drifting of snow. Some drifts are near 4 feet deep.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The first significant snow storm of the 2010-11 winter season dumped between 2 and 12 inches of snow on eastern Kentucky on December 12th and 13th. The highest snowfall totals occurred in Bell, Lee, and Leslie, and McCreary counties where 10-12 inches were reported. There were several culprits for this snow event, as areas of low pressure moving across the lower Great Lakes and up the eastern slopes of the Appalachian Mountains combined forces over the Ohio and Tennessee valleys. The highest snowfall totals occurred along the Kentucky River basin as an intense band of moderate to heavy snowfall remained in place there during the overnight hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter reported a snowfall of 2.1 inches in Calvin.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure tracking from the Plains northeastward into the Great Lakes brought a period of moderate to heavy snow to parts of central Illinois from the evening of January 6th through the morning of January 7th. Once the snow subsided, gusty northwesterly winds created considerable blowing and drifting across the area through the night of January 7th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system moved from northern Old Mexico into New Mexico Wednesday night, January 27th, 2010.  This winter system then plowed east-northeast through Kansas, Texas and Oklahoma Thursday and early Friday, January 28th and 29th.  This brought significant snowfall to much of southwest and south central Kansas.  The precipitation began as light snow late Wednesday night, then picked up and continued as heavy snow for much of Thursday and Thursday night.  While snow persisted Friday morning, January 29th, in parts of our southeastern CWA, not much additional accumulation occurred.  Reports received Friday morning, January 29th, revealed a 5 to 20 mile wide swath of 7 to 11 inches of snowfall fell along an axis from near Hudson in northeastern Stafford County, to north of Haviland in Kiowa County, through northern parts of both Ford and Gray Counties, to just north of Big Bow in extreme northeastern Stanton County.  On either side of this heavy band of snow, an area of 4 to 6 inches of snow fell, basically south of a line from Shallow Water in southeast Scott County to Brownell in northeast Ness County to Pfeifer in southeast Ellis County, as well as north of a line from Elkhart in southeast Morton County to near Ashland in Clark county to near Sawyer in southeastern Pratt County.  In northern parts of DDC���s CWA, as well as in southeastern parts, 2 to 4 inches of snow fell.  The highest snowfall report received from this event was 11 inches at Ingalls in Gray County, with drifts as high as 5 feet in the Dodge City area also reported.  Winds during the event were from the north to northwest at 20 to 35 mph, which caused many areas of deep drifting and widespread travel problems.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 7.5 inches was reported 11 miles northeast of Ashland.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Lake effect snow developed as arctic air swept over Lake Michigan on north northwest winds.  Heavy snow showers resulted in localized accumulations of 12 to 18 inches across western portions of Van Buren, Allegan, Mason, Oceana and northern Muskegon counties.  Little snow fell roughly 30 miles and further east of the lakeshore.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Localized snowfall amounts of up to 6 to 8 inches were reported across far western portions of Ottawa county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front crossed the region on New Year���s Day. A broad area of lake effect snows develop along the south shores of Lakes Erie and Ontario late on the first. Some narrow intense bands developed in this area and extended up to twenty miles inland. The activity continued through Saturday (3rd) and then strengthened in place Saturday Night as a large area of moisture spiraled around a massive coastal storm off New England.  A general burst of moderate to heavy snow accompanied this synoptic feature as it dropped south and southwest across the entire region during Sunday, then finally the lake effect weakened and retreated to near the lakes again Sunday night.  This event was unique in many ways, most notably in the large amounts of snow off Lake Ontario back across much of the Niagara frontier. A general one to two feet fell over two days, with up to 30 inches around Niagara Falls. Another area of very heavy snow focused on Wayne to Oswego County where two to three feet fell. The Rochester area caught a bit less, but still up to 18 inches near the Lake.  Off Lake Erie, two feet or more fell near Chautauqua Lake from Mayville to Jamestown. |Specific snowfall totals Off Lake Erie included:  Mayville 31���; Jamestown 28���; and Perrysburg 26���. Off Lake Ontario, the reports included: 42��� at Fulton; 38��� at Lacona; 36��� at Marion; 34��� at Scriba; 32��� at Hannibal; 31��� at Niagara Falls; 30��� at Pulaski; 26��� at North Tonawanda, Kent and Williamson; 24��� at Lockport; 22��� at Oswego; 19��� at North Amherst; 16��� at Perry; 14��� at Tonawanda; and 9��� to 18��� in Rochester (from north to south across the city).

Abundant rain advanced north into the region in advance of an area of low pressure to the west while a frontal boundary remained draped over the region. An average of 2 to 5 inches of rain fell from this system onto an already saturated ground from recent snow melt and rainfall. The heavy rain contributed to widespread flash flooding, mudslides, areal flooding, and river flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain prompted a stream to leave its banks and cause flash flooding. Pico Road was closed due to the flash flooding. Damage values are estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow and gusty winds impacted portions of northwest and southwest Montana in both the valleys and mountains. Total snowfall amounts ranged from 6 to 8 inches in the valleys to over a foot in the mountains in northwest Montana. Gusty north winds caused blowing and drifting of snow which created dangerous driving conditions on roadways and caused local schools to close in Flathead County. Power outages were also reported in Flathead County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Montana Department of Transportation declared severe driving conditions on I-90 Deer Lodge to Phosphate, I-90 Deer Lodge to Warm Springs, and US 12 Garrison to Avon due to very strong winds and blowing snow. Chains were required on McDonald Pass from blowing and drifting of snow. Wind speeds at Garrison weather station were recorded at 27 mph with gusts to 35 mph at 716 PM. Wind speeds at Helmville MT-200 weather station were recorded at 33 mph gusting to 43 mph at 756 PM.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Localized freezing rain caused some schools to delay opening and closed a portion of I-90 in west central Montana on 1/12/2010.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Freezing rain caused very slick roadways and closed the Alberton Schools.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Ice Jam on the Salmon River caused flooding to many county roads|4 to 8 miles north of Salmon Idaho.  The water also entered about 5 to 10 home owners yards and driveways.  One home located 4 1/2 miles north of Salmon in the community of Carmen had water enter their home with damages estimated at $10,000 to $20,000.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice jam buildup on the Salmon River caused waters to rise and flood 4 to 8 miles north of Salmon near the Carmen area and flood homes. A camp ground on a gravel bar near the river was under water; the first time in two decades. The Morgan Bar recreation area was also submerged in water. Local county roads were flooded in the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fast moving storm system tracked southeast across the Central Plains producing a swath of 3 to 6 inches of snow along with strong northwest winds.  The very dry nature of the snow combined with strong northwest winds to produce near zero visibilities on area roadways during the evening hours of January 6th.  The area already had a powdery snowpack of 6 to 12 inches which also served to enhance the blowing and drifting of snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Spotter estimates 4.5 inches of new snow.  The snow is now blowing and drifting with near zero visibility.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On January 6th and 7th 2010, a potent storm system moved across the region. This storm brought widespread snowfall of 3 to 6 inches to eastern Kansas and much of the northern half of Missouri. The storm system also brought bitterly cold temperatures, strong northwesterly winds and brutal wind chills to the area. Northwest winds of around 20 to 25 mph and gusts to around 35 mph were common across the region Thursday afternoon, creating significant blowing and drifting snow. These winds combined with temperatures in the single digits and lower teens, to produce wind chill values of -5 to -15 degrees during the daytime hours Thursday. ||The wind gradually decreased through Friday, as the storm system moved northeast of the region. Very cold temperatures overspread the area behind the storm system. Temperatures Friday morning ranged from 5 to -5 degrees, with Friday afternoon readings mainly in the 5 to 10 degree range.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Up to 5 inches of snow was reported in Leavenworth. Strong gusty northwest winds caused blowing and drifting snow.

CZ_NAME: TANGIER SOUND AND THE INLAND WATERS SURROUNDING BLOODSWORTH ISLAND
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High pressure over the western Atlantic continued to usher in hot and humid air due to a southwest flow. An upper-level disturbance in the zonal flow triggered showers and thunderstorms across portions of the Tidal Potomac River and Chesapeake Bay. Moderate amounts of instability due to the hot and humid air mass caused some thunderstorms to produce gusty winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust of 34 knots was estimated about two miles west of Smith Island.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper-level disturbance and its associated cold front moved into Maryland on the 25th. Hot and humid conditions ahead of the front led to high amounts of instability. Showers and thunderstorms developed along and ahead of the cold front. Due to the high amounts of instability, thunderstorms were able to mix down strong winds from aloft causing significant amounts of damage across portions of Maryland.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A fatality occurred due to a lightning strike at the Watkins Pond Community Garden in Rockville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level disturbance combined with weak instability to drive a squall line across portions of Southwest Virginia. Very strong winds aloft were able to mix down to the surface leading to many reports of downed trees. This line weakened as it approached the mountains, with no severe reports east of the mountains.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong thunderstorm winds blew down power lines. Damage amounts are estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A series of cold and moist storms moved through Utah in the last week of October. These storms dropped the first significant snowfall of the season on the higher terrain across the state, and also caused strong gusty winds in valleys across northern Utah.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Wasatch Plateau and Book Cliffs received between 1.00 and 2.00 inches of liquid equivalent precipitation in the first storm of the season, with much of that falling as snow in the highest elevations of the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Moist northwest flow off Lake Michigan combined with terrain effects brought yet another round of light snow to eastern Kentucky on January 5th. The highest snowfall amount recorded occurred in Letcher county. Two to three inches of snow fell in a 24 hour period, with isolated accumulations of 4-5 inches across the higher terrain. All in all 1-3 inches of snow fell in the affected counties from late in the day on January 4th through late in the morning on the 5th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The water plant reports 2 to 3 inches of snow on the ground in Inez with light flurries.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and then through the mid Atlantic region on January 29th and 30th. The snow first began falling across eastern Kentucky during the late afternoon and evening hours of January 29th as the storm moved across central Tennessee. The snow finally came to an end late in the day on January 30th as the area of low pressure moved up the east coast. Snowfall amounts of 4-8 inches were quite common around the area, with accumulations as high as 11 inches reported on Black Mountain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Highway Dept estimated that 5 to 7 inches of snow fell across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stable air mass was in place across much of the area in the wake of a line of storms from earlier in the day. Increasing instability and an approaching upper level wave set the stage for thunderstorms to develop. A few of these took on super-cell characteristics across Cass and White counties. A storm spotter photographed a tornado northeast of Wolcott, Indiana which developed over an open field.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Local media reported a viewer measuring a 60 mph wind gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stable air mass was in place across much of the area in the wake of a line of storms from earlier in the day. Increasing instability and an approaching upper level wave set the stage for thunderstorms to develop. A few of these took on super-cell characteristics across Cass and White counties. A storm spotter photographed a tornado northeast of Wolcott, Indiana which developed over an open field.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Local media relayed a report of a tornado being observed northeast of Wolcott by a trained spotter. The spotter subsequently sent a photograph and video of the tornado. The spotter stated that it touched down in an open field and was on the ground for less than a minute, causing no appreciable damage. The width of the circulation has been estimated from a photograph of the debris cloud. As no damage was reported, a intensity of EF0 with winds of 65 mph will be assigned.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening area of low pressure tracked eastward near the Interstate 80 corridor in Indiana and Ohio. Precipitation initially began as rain on December 11th, before transitioning to moderate snow on the 12th as colder air filtered in on the backside of this low pressure system. Snowfall totals generally ranged between 3 and 6 inches. Wind gusts of 25 to 35 mph created widespread blowing and drifting snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rain changed to snow during the morning hours of December 12th and continued through the entire day. Snowfall totals generally ranged between 2 and 5 inches, with a trained spotter in LaGrange reporting nearly 3 inches of total snow accumulation. Winds increased Sunday afternoon into Monday morning, with gusts of 25 to 35 mph at times. This, combined with the fallen snow, created widespread blowing and drifting snow that led to numerous car accidents and school closings across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening area of low pressure tracked eastward near the Interstate 80 corridor in Indiana and Ohio. Precipitation initially began as rain on December 11th, before transitioning to moderate snow on the 12th as colder air filtered in on the backside of this low pressure system. Snowfall totals generally ranged between 3 and 6 inches. Wind gusts of 25 to 35 mph created widespread blowing and drifting snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rain changed to snow during the morning hours of December 12th and continued through the entire day. An intense lake effect snow band moved in Sunday night, with heavy snowfall and reduced visibilities. A CoCoRaHs observer 6 miles east-southeast of North Judson reported 9.5 inches of total snow accumulation by early Monday morning. Winds increased Sunday afternoon into Monday morning, with gusts of 25 to 35 mph at times. This, combined with the fallen snow, created widespread blowing and drifting snow that led to numerous car accidents and school closings across the region.
