EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Between the evening of the 30th and the morning of the 31st, two separate lines of thunderstorms produced significant severe weather across southwest Missouri including damaging wind, large hail, and deadly tornadoes. The first round of storms lifted out of Arkansas late on the evening of the 30th and the second round moved out of western Kansas shortly before daybreak on the 31st.

Record Snowfall occurred across the greater Burlington area on January 2nd into January 3rd.||A powerful ocean storm southeast of Nova Scotia during the late afternoon of January 2nd, retrograded into the Gulf of Maine near Rockport, Maine by the morning of January 3rd and then proceeded to return to the Atlantic Ocean during the afternoon of January 3rd.||Wraparound snows moved into northern Vermont during the afternoon and evening hours of January 2nd and continued through the afternoon of January 3rd. The windward side (west) of the various mountain ranges in Vermont witnessed the heaviest snowfall due to upslope conditions with the leeward side (east) received less snow due to downslope. In addition, some training of mesoscale snow bands, likely a result of upslope and convergence within the Champlain Valley of Vermont accounted for record snowfall in the Burlington area. ||Favorable upslope regions received 8 to 18 inches of snowfall with over 30 inches in the greater Burlington area. Meanwhile downslope regions received 2 to 6 inches of snowfall. In addition, brisk northwest winds of 15 to 25 mph with higher gusts caused considerable blowing and drfiting of the snow with 4 to 5 foot snow drifts reported.||A record 33.1 inches of snow fell with this storm at Burlington Int'l Airport in South Burlington, which surpassed the old record of 29.8 inches that occurred on December 25-28 in 1969. ||Some other specific snowfall totals; 30 inches in Essex Junction and Colchester (Chittenden county), 25 inches in Monkton (Addison county) and Milton (Chittenden county), 24 inches in Charlotte (Chittenden county), 22 inches in Jeffersonville (Lamoille county), Underhill and Jericho (Chittenden county), 18 inches in Canaan (Essex county) and Sheldon Springs (Franklin county), 16 inches in Cambridge (Lamoille county), 14 inches in Barton (Orleans county), Danby (Rutland county) and Lincoln (Addison county).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By late afternoon of July 17th, an area of low pressure was located over the far southern Red River Valley with a warm front extending to its east. Temperatures had topped out in the middle 80s with dew points in the lower 70s. Thunderstorms flared up along and north of the warm front, mainly affecting southeast North Dakota and west central Minnesota. Large hail was reported along with a few strong winds gusts. Heavy amounts of rain also fell along the Highway 10 corridor in west central Minnesota, mainly between Detroit Lakes and Wadena.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and then through the mid Atlantic region on January 29th and 30th. The snow first began falling across eastern Kentucky during the late afternoon and evening hours of January 29th as the storm moved across central Tennessee. The snow finally came to an end late in the day on January 30th as the area of low pressure moved up the east coast. Snowfall amounts of 4-8 inches were quite common around the area, with accumulations as high as 11 inches reported on Black Mountain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Five inches of snow fell near Prestonsburg.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low level jet and good warm advection helped to spawn a couple strong thunderstorms in the early morning hours of the 12th. Then there was a brief break before strong thunderstorms began to flare up again by the early afternoon. Thunderstorms kept firing north of a warm front located over northeast South Dakota and southern Minnesota, as the low level jet and warm advection stay strong through the day. These storms produced very heavy rainfall rates and some flash flooding as well as sporadic reports of strong winds into the evening.
Strong east winds affected the east Puget Sound lowlands and southwest interior.  Meanwhile high winds were recorded on Hurricane Ridge in the Olympics.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind sensors on Hurricane Ridge operated by the Northwest Avalanche Center recorded 60 mph sustained wind with gusts in the 80s.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent and slow moving area of low pressure dumped heavy rainfall on portions of eastern Kentucky on January 24th and 25th. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Unseasonably warm temperatures moved into southern New England ahead of a cold front which allowed for excellent atmospheric mixing.  This resulted in strong to damaging winds across much of eastern Massachusetts and Rhode Island.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A weather station at an amateur radio operator's home recorded a wind gust to 52 mph.  Several trees in Middleboro were downed, including one that landed on a car.  Trees were also downed in Hanover, Halifax, and Brockton.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Abundant rain advanced north into the region in advance of an area of low pressure to the west while a frontal boundary remained draped over the region. An average of 2 to 5 inches of rain fell from this system onto an already saturated ground from recent snow melt and rainfall. The heavy rain contributed to widespread flash flooding, mudslides, areal flooding, and river flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding caused a portion of Turkey Mountain Road to wash out. Damage values are estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Very cold north winds resulted in an extended period of locally heavy lake effect snow in Northwest Lower Michigan.  The first dominant band of snow produced 6 to 7 inches of accumulation near and south of Kalkaska by morning on New Years Day.  A stronger band reformed along the Lake Michigan coast during the day, dumping 10 inches of snow on part of the city of Manistee.  By evening of the 1st,  bands brought 2 to 3 inch per hour accumulations northwest of Traverse City, and near Williamsburg.  Finally, on the night of the 2nd, Beulah and Lake Ann got into the act, with localized 6 to 9 inch accumulations.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front crossed the region on New Year���s Day. A broad area of lake effect snows develop along the south shores of Lakes Erie and Ontario late on the first. Some narrow intense bands developed in this area and extended up to twenty miles inland. The activity continued through Saturday (3rd) and then strengthened in place Saturday Night as a large area of moisture spiraled around a massive coastal storm off New England.  A general burst of moderate to heavy snow accompanied this synoptic feature as it dropped south and southwest across the entire region during Sunday, then finally the lake effect weakened and retreated to near the lakes again Sunday night.  This event was unique in many ways, most notably in the large amounts of snow off Lake Ontario back across much of the Niagara frontier. A general one to two feet fell over two days, with up to 30 inches around Niagara Falls. Another area of very heavy snow focused on Wayne to Oswego County where two to three feet fell. The Rochester area caught a bit less, but still up to 18 inches near the Lake.  Off Lake Erie, two feet or more fell near Chautauqua Lake from Mayville to Jamestown. |Specific snowfall totals Off Lake Erie included:  Mayville 31���; Jamestown 28���; and Perrysburg 26���. Off Lake Ontario, the reports included: 42��� at Fulton; 38��� at Lacona; 36��� at Marion; 34��� at Scriba; 32��� at Hannibal; 31��� at Niagara Falls; 30��� at Pulaski; 26��� at North Tonawanda, Kent and Williamson; 24��� at Lockport; 22��� at Oswego; 19��� at North Amherst; 16��� at Perry; 14��� at Tonawanda; and 9��� to 18��� in Rochester (from north to south across the city).

An unusually cold Arctic airmass came across the area on January 6th and stayed through January 9th. This area has not seen a cold airmass like this since December 2005, and even February 1996 before that.  Besides the cold temperatures, this Arctic airmass brought in very strong winds throughout the area on the evening of January 6th and on Thursday, January the 7th.  The strong winds combined with the very cold temperatures creating dangerous wind chills. Wind chills through this cold outbreak created dangerous situations for people, animals, and property that were outdoors for a long period of time. Several schools across the area were cancelled or delayed, waterline mains bursted and slick driving conditions were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Temperatures in the single digits combined with wind chills of minus 15 to minus 20 degrees led to numerous water lines to burst across the county.  The city of Wichita water department reported 160 calls of burst water lines or burst water meters. The extreme wind chills also led to numerous schools in and around Wichita to cancel on Friday, January 8th, as minus 20 degree wind chills made it unsafe for children to wait at the bus stops.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An ocean storm brought significant amounts of snow to Plymouth County, the Cape and Islands.  A deep layer of moisture over this region aided in producing the highest snowfall Southern New England had seen to date this winter.  Average accumulations ran from 2 to 4 inches in southern Bristol County and Boston to 8 to 10 inches in eastern Plymouth County and Cape Cod.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Anywhere from 4 to 8 inches of snow fell in western Plymouth County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cutoff low moved out of Arizona and across New Mexico with plenty of moisture in place from previous storm systems. Snow levels started out around 8000 feet and quickly fell behind strong cold front to below 5000 feet. Snowfall of up to 11 inches was reported in Cloudcroft.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Maximum snowfall reported was 11.0 inches in Cloudcroft.  Other snowfall totals were 9.3 inches 5 miles northeast of Cloudcroft, 8.7 inches 2 miles southwest of Cloudcroft and 7.5 inches in Sunspot.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed around the Langdon (ND) area in the early evening and tracked to the southeast. Initially the storms dropped some large hail, but as the storms approached the Grand Forks/East Grand Forks area they produced some strong gusts of wind.

By late in the day on the 7th, an east-west lying warm front had set up just north of the South Dakota border, extending eastward into west central Minnesota. South of the warm front, temperatures were in the mid to upper 80s with dew points in the lower 70s. Thunderstorms formed along and north of the warm front and several produced tornadoes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This tornado began in Richland County, North Dakota, at 625 pm CDT, where it had a path length of 2.5 miles. It continued in Wilkin County, Minnesota, where it finally lifted about 2.5 miles southwest of Doran. The total path length was roughly five miles and peak winds were estimated at 175 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By late in the day on the 7th, an east-west lying warm front had set up just north of the South Dakota border, extending eastward into west central Minnesota. South of the warm front, temperatures were in the mid to upper 80s with dew points in the lower 70s. Thunderstorms formed along and north of the warm front and several produced tornadoes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This tornado tracked for about a mile through mainly open fields. This was the latter of three distinct tornadoes which occurred from at least four distinct funnel clouds in Wilkin County during a roughly 15 to 20 minute period. Peak winds were estimated at 75 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By late in the day on the 7th, an east-west lying warm front had set up just north of the South Dakota border, extending eastward into west central Minnesota. EVENT_NARRATIVE: This tornado tracked intermittently for about 4 miles, mainly over open fields. However, the tornado did knock down some trees in shelterbelts and left swirls in crops. The tornado and debris cloud was viewed from near Elbow Lake. Peak winds were estimated at 90 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Pacific winter storm produced moderate valley rain and mountain snow to much of southeast Arizona. Heavy snow combined with strong winds to produce significant blowing and drifting at the higher elevations. Strong gusty winds also affected many valley locations during the evening hours of the 19th and the early morning hours of the 20th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three and one half inches of snow fell at the base of the Chiricahua Mountains at 5300 feet with considerably more snow at the top of the mountains.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure east of Nantucket resulted in a long duration storm across southern New England.  A long period of easterly winds, coupled with astronomically high tides, aided in producing coastal flooding along the east coast of Massachusetts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Loring Road and Commercial, Bridge, and Forrester Streets in Salem were flooded with seawater.  In addition, the commuter rail parking lot in Salem was flooded.  Waves at Deveraux Beach in Marblehead overtopped the seawall, flooding an adjacent parking lot.  Lynn Shore Drive in Lynn was flooded by waves overtopping the seawall.  The intersection of Liberty and Tibet Roads in Danvers was closed because of flooding.  Portions of Route 107 in Saugus were flooded.  Essex and Western Avenues in Gloucester were flooded, as well as Causeway Street and Thatcher Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure east of Nantucket resulted in a long duration storm across southern New England.  A long period of easterly winds, coupled with astronomically high tides, aided in producing coastal flooding along the east coast of Massachusetts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Shore Road in Revere and Morrisey Boulevard in Boston were closed because of coastal flooding.  Washington Avenue in Winthrop was flooded with two feet of water.  Waves overtopped the seawall on Castle Island, flowing onto the sidewalks.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On December 24th, Christmas Eve, a low pressure system traversed along the Gulf Of Mexico. Moisture streamed up into the area but the Jackson CWA was spared  the heavier snowfall as that occurred further east. The event was worthy of Winter Weather Advisories with a Winter Storm Warning issued for the higher elevations in Harlan and Letcher counties. A powerful east coast low pressure developed and traveled up the east coast. The fully developed low pressure system brought northerly flow into eastern Kentucky and created an extended upslope event. The event prompted the continuance of the advisories and winter storm warnings into December 27th till noon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two and a half inches of snow fell overnight 2 miles north of Prestonsburg.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracked through the Ohio Valley before redeveloping off the Mid-Atlantic Coast. Most of the snow and ice fell across the Shenandoah Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trace of ice accumulation was reported near Grottoes. Snow and sleet also accumulated up to two tenths of an inch near Massanutten.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On the afternoon of February 23rd through the evening hours of February 24th, the combination of a large developing upper atmospheric low pressure system across the lower Great Lakes and Ohio River Valley with a surface low south of New England accounted for a prolonged fetch of sub-tropical Atlantic moisture to feed back into marginally cold air across New England and New York.||A heavy wet snow fell across the eastern Adirondacks and Champlain Valley of New York that resulted in snowfall accumulations of 6 to 18 inches with the higher amounts within the Champlain Valley. As a strong upper low moved across the area, flurries and bands of light snowfall developed during the early morning hours on December 26th, affecting much of Central Alabama through the day. Flurries as far south as Troy, one inch accumulations across northwest Central Alabama, and a dusting at many locations in between were reported. Gusty northwesterly winds combined with the light snowfall to bring visibilities down to around one mile at times. ||Roadways were slick from the Christmas Day snowfall. As the additional light snowfall combined with temperatures near or below freezing, travel conditions remained hazardous. Travel was discouraged across much of the area. With below freezing temperatures, snow remained on the ground for several days in parts of north Central Alabama.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: As a result of light snowfall, roadways remained icy making travel hazardous.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread light to moderate snow fell during the daylight hours of January 7th as an Alberta Clipper tracked through the region.  Snowfall amounts generally ranged between 4 and 6 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Light snow developed around daybreak January 7th and became moderate to heavy  during the morning and early afternoon hours as a clipper system moved through the region.  The snow tapered off to just a few lingering snow showers and flurries by late in the afternoon.  Total snow accumulations of 5 to 6 inches were common across the county, with a report of 5.0 inches at Peru.  The accumulating snow and low visibilities led to a few accidents and slide-offs across the area, along with cancellations of local events.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On December 24th, Christmas Eve, a low pressure system traversed along the Gulf Of Mexico. Moisture streamed up into the area but the Jackson CWA was spared  the heavier snowfall as that occurred further east. The event was worthy of Winter Weather Advisories with a Winter Storm Warning issued for the higher elevations in Harlan and Letcher counties. A powerful east coast low pressure developed and traveled up the east coast. The fully developed low pressure system brought northerly flow into eastern Kentucky and created an extended upslope event. The event prompted the continuance of the advisories and winter storm warnings into December 27th till noon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three inches of snow fell in Whitesburg overnight, with a total snow depth of 6 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By late afternoon of July 17th, an area of low pressure was located over the far southern Red River Valley with a warm front extending to its east. Temperatures had topped out in the middle 80s with dew points in the lower 70s. Thunderstorms flared up along and north of the warm front, mainly affecting southeast North Dakota and west central Minnesota. Large hail was reported along with a few strong winds gusts. Heavy amounts of rain also fell along the Highway 10 corridor in west central Minnesota, mainly between Detroit Lakes and Wadena.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A small ride at the Clay County fair was damaged due to strong winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A persistent thunderstorm cell along the Canadian border produced a tornado and several reports of strong winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sixteen inch diameter trees were snapped. It may have been accompanied by a funnel cloud, but it was rain wrapped and hard to see.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A persistent thunderstorm cell along the Canadian border produced a tornado and several reports of strong winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This tornado began in Towner County at 820 pm CDT. The tornado tracked for about 20 miles total, about 10 miles in Towner County and then about 10 miles in Cavalier County. During much of this track the tornado was likely enveloped in heavy rains and strong downburst winds with the funnel briefly visible at times. The tornado broke down two wooden power poles and numerous trees and tree limbs along its route. Peak winds were estimated at 95 mph.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rainfall amounts from 4 to 5 inches produced flooding to area fields and farm access roads.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Street flooding was reported in Egeland.

A strong cold front crossed the region on New Year���s Day. A broad area of lake effect snows develop along the south shores of Lakes Erie and Ontario late on the first. Some narrow intense bands developed in this area and extended up to twenty miles inland. The activity continued through Saturday (3rd) and then strengthened in place Saturday Night as a large area of moisture spiraled around a massive coastal storm off New England.  A general burst of moderate to heavy snow accompanied this synoptic feature as it dropped south and southwest across the entire region during Sunday, then finally the lake effect weakened and retreated to near the lakes again Sunday night.  This event was unique in many ways, most notably in the large amounts of snow off Lake Ontario back across much of the Niagara frontier. A general one to two feet fell over two days, with up to 30 inches around Niagara Falls. Another area of very heavy snow focused on Wayne to Oswego County where two to three feet fell. The Rochester area caught a bit less, but still up to 18 inches near the Lake.  Off Lake Erie, two feet or more fell near Chautauqua Lake from Mayville to Jamestown. |Specific snowfall totals Off Lake Erie included:  Mayville 31���; Jamestown 28���; and Perrysburg 26���. Unseasonably warm temperatures moved into southern New England ahead of a cold front which allowed for excellent atmospheric mixing. This resulted in strong to damaging winds across much of eastern Massachusetts and Rhode Island.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A weather station at a spotter's home in Cranston recorded a wind gust of 51 mph.  A tree in East Providence was downed.  In Cranston, a telephone pole was downed.  A 30 foot tall pine tree in Providence was downed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong storm system tracking northeast from the Gulf of Mexico spread heavy snow and freezing rain into Central North Carolina the evening of January 29th. The snow continued into the morning hours of January 30th. Between 5 to 10 inches of snow blanketed areas along and north of Highway 64 with up to a foot of snow reported along the Virginia border. Locations across the southern piedmont, southern coastal plain and sandhills experienced a mix of snow and freezing rain. Freezing rain accumulations ranged from one-eighth to a half inch of ice.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Around 3 inches of snow fell across the county in addition to a trace of freezing rain.  Several vehicle accidents and a number of power outages were reported. Due to the cold temperatures icy road conditions persisted for several days resulting in the closure of schools and businesses.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong winds developed as a pressure gradient around an area of low pressure north of the area increased. The result was an isolated area of damaging winds over Bedford County Virginia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: At a location one mile south-southeast of Thaxton, VA, winds with gusts estimated between 50 and 60 mph toppled some pine trees ten inches in diameter. Damage values are estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An arctic cold front move through southeast West Virginia the morning of January 8, 2010. Behind this front, increasing northwest winds with Great Lake moisture helped to generate up to ten inches of snow in the western slopes of Greenbrier County West Virginia. The bulk of the snow fell through the morning hours on January 9, but additional light accumulating snow continue through the early afternoon of January 10.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The snow storm produced ten inches of snow at Quinwood, West Virginia.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold high pressure was in place across the area as warm, moist air overspread the region in association with a warm front moving north across the region. The result was rain that fell onto sub-freezing surface that produced up to one-quarter inch of ice.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accretions totaled 0.25 inches in both Frankford and Ronceverte.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Abundant rain advanced north into the region in advance of an area of low pressure to the west while a frontal boundary remained draped over the region. An average of 2 to 5 inches of rain fell from this system onto an already saturated ground from recent snow melt and rainfall. The heavy rain contributed to widespread flash flooding, mudslides, areal flooding, and river flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain prompted a flash flood that closed a portion of Oregon Hill Road.  Damage values are estimated.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong winds were reported at the Garibaldi NOS site with sustained winds of 43 kts and gusts to 51 kts.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Pacific weather system brought strong winds to the northern and central Oregon Coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong winds were reported on the Yaquina Bridge with sustained winds of 36 kts and gusts to 48 kts. Strong winds were also reported at the Newport C-MAN station with sustained winds of 38 kts and at Lincoln City with a gust to 57 kts.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Pacific weather system brought heavy rainfall to the area in mid December causing flooding on local rivers.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rainfall over the area caused the Grays River near Rosburg to overflow its banks.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A series of strong weather systems brought heavy rain to northwest Oregon causing flooding on local rivers.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain caused the Luckiamute River to rise above flood stage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure east of Nantucket resulted in a long duration storm across southern New England.  A long period of easterly winds, coupled with astronomically high tides, aided in producing coastal flooding along the east coast of Massachusetts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rockland and Kilby Streets in Hingham were flooded with seawater. Hull Shore Drive was closed because of eight to twelve foot waves crashing over the sea wall.  Also in Hull, Moreland and Nantasket Avenues were both flooded.  The intersection of Fore River Avenue and Holbrook Road in Weymouth was flooded with one foot of water.  Also in Weymouth, Fort Point Road between Beacon and Birch Streets was closed because of flooding up to one foot deep.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure east of Nantucket resulted in a long duration storm across southern New England.  A long period of easterly winds, coupled with astronomically high tides, aided in producing coastal flooding along the east coast of Massachusetts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several streets in the Hummarock section of Scituate were flooded.  Glades Road in the Minot section of Scituate was impassable.  First Parish Road was flooded with three feet of water and Front Street and Baileys Way were impassable.  Route 139 in Marshfield was closed due to flooding by the Green Harbor Yacht Club.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong storm system tracking northeast from the Gulf of Mexico spread heavy snow and freezing rain into Central North Carolina the evening of January 29th. The snow continued into the morning hours of January 30th. Between 5 to 10 inches of snow blanketed areas along and north of Highway 64 with up to a foot of snow reported along the Virginia border. Locations across the southern piedmont, southern coastal plain and sandhills experienced a mix of snow and freezing rain. Freezing rain accumulations ranged from one-eighth to a half inch of ice.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 5 to 6 inches of snow fell across the county. Several automobile accidents were reported. Due to the cold temperatures icy road conditions persisted for several days.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong storm system tracking northeast from the Gulf of Mexico spread heavy snow and freezing rain into Central North Carolina the evening of January 29th. The snow continued into the morning hours of January 30th. Between 5 to 10 inches of snow blanketed areas along and north of Highway 64 with up to a foot of snow reported along the Virginia border. Locations across the southern piedmont, southern coastal plain and sandhills experienced a mix of snow and freezing rain. Freezing rain accumulations ranged from one-eighth to a half inch of ice.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between one eight to a quarter of an inch of freezing rain fell across the county in addition to around one inch of snow. Over 2500 people were without power in the county. Emergency rooms reported numerous minor injuries due to falls on the ice.  Several automobile accidents were reported. Due to the cold temperatures icy road conditions persisted for several days.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracked through the Ohio Valley before redeveloping off the Mid-Atlantic Coast. High pressure to the north kept just enough cold air for precipitation that was associated with this low to fall in the from of snow and ice.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow and sleet accumulation was estimated to be around two inches in western Mineral County. A glaze of ice was also estimated from freezing rain.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulation from freezing rain totaled around one quarter of an inch in Bayard. Snow and sleet totaled around one half inch at Bayard.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper-level low passed through the Mid-Atlantic triggering snow on the 30th. The heaviest snow fell during the late morning and afternoon hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six inches of snow fell in Frostburg.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper-level low passed through the Mid-Atlantic triggering snow on the 30th. The heaviest snow fell during the late morning and afternoon hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow reports between five and six inches were received throughout the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system tracked acros Northern Florida which produced heavy snow on the north side of the storm system.  Snow fell from the Florida panhandle northeast to Virginia.  Amounts in the CSRA ranged from 4-7 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: EM reported 4-6 inches of snow across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a strong upper low moved across the area, flurries and bands of light snowfall developed during the early morning hours on December 26th, affecting much of Central Alabama through the day. Flurries as far south as Troy, one inch accumulations across northwest Central Alabama, and a dusting at many locations in between were reported. Gusty northwesterly winds combined with the light snowfall to bring visibilities down to around one mile at times. ||Roadways were slick from the Christmas Day snowfall. As the additional light snowfall combined with temperatures near or below freezing, travel conditions remained hazardous. Travel was discouraged across much of the area. With below freezing temperatures, snow remained on the ground for several days in parts of north Central Alabama.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: As a result of light snowfall, roadways remained icy making travel hazardous.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Although light snow did fall off and on on January 8th, most of the snowfall reports received at the Jackson weather office were 24 hour totals. The bulk of the snow that fell across eastern Kentucky occurred from late morning on January 7th through 2 or 3 am on January 8th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four inches of snow fell 3 miles south of Prestonsburg. Most of the snow fell from late in the morning on January 7th and 2 or 3 am on January 8th.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three inches of snow fell 4 miles east of Frenchburg. Most of the snow fell between early in the morning of January 7th and 1 or 2 am on January 8th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On December 24th, Christmas Eve, a low pressure system traversed along the Gulf Of Mexico. Moisture streamed up into the area but the Jackson CWA was spared  the heavier snowfall as that occurred further east. The event was worthy of Winter Weather Advisories with a Winter Storm Warning issued for the higher elevations in Harlan and Letcher counties. A powerful east coast low pressure developed and traveled up the east coast. The fully developed low pressure system brought northerly flow into eastern Kentucky and created an extended upslope event. The event prompted the continuance of the advisories and winter storm warnings into December 27th till noon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two and a half inches of snow had fallen as of 730 am, with another half inch having fallen since then.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Daytime air temperatures reached between 98 and 106 while heat indices reached the 110 to 115 degree range. Nighttime temperatures only fell into the 75 to 80 degree range through this period which was separated from the first episode by a brief 48 hour period.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Daytime air temperatures reached between 98 and 106 while heat indices reached the 110 to 115 degree range. Nighttime temperatures only fell into the 75 to 80 degree range through this period.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As an upper level disturbance lifted into eastern North Dakota, a semi-circle of thunderstorms formed around its northern and eastern periphery. As a segment of these storms moved north of Mayville, they produced a brief tornado near Holmes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado struck a farmstead in southern Grand Forks County, damaging a large well constructed equipment shed. The tornado traveled over a shelterbelt along the west edge of the property causing considerable damage. Several pieces of farm equipment were moved and flipped. An empty grain bin was removed from its foundation and lofted 300 yards, with much of the bin landing in the northwest corner of the shelterbelt.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low level jet and good warm advection helped to spawn a couple strong thunderstorms in the early morning hours of the 12th. Then there was a brief break before strong thunderstorms began to flare up again by the early afternoon. Thunderstorms kept firing north of a warm front located over northeast South Dakota and southern Minnesota, as the low level jet and warm advection stay strong through the day. These storms produced very heavy rainfall rates and some flash flooding as well as sporadic reports of strong winds into the evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Streets flooded in the town of Sabin. In rural areas around Sabin, ditches filled with water and flooded several rural roads.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Between the evening of the 30th and the morning of the 31st, two separate lines of thunderstorms produced significant severe weather across southwest Missouri including damaging wind, large hail, and deadly tornadoes. The first round of storms lifted out of Arkansas late on the evening of the 30th and the second round moved out of western Kansas shortly before daybreak on the 31st.

Between the evening of the 30th and the morning of the 31st, two separate lines of thunderstorms produced significant severe weather across southwest Missouri including damaging wind, large hail, and deadly tornadoes. The first round of storms lifted out of Arkansas late on the evening of the 30th and the second round moved out of western Kansas shortly before daybreak on the 31st.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A lightning strike struck a large two story home just north of Lebanon.  The resultant fire burned down the home and was a complete lost.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and then through the mid Atlantic region on January 29th and 30th. The snow first began falling across eastern Kentucky during the late afternoon and evening hours of January 29th as the storm moved across central Tennessee. The snow finally came to an end late in the day on January 30th as the area of low pressure moved up the east coast. Snowfall amounts of 4-8 inches were quite common around the area, with accumulations as high as 11 inches reported on Black Mountain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An NWS employee measured a storm total snowfall of 7.9 inches with a current snow depth of 7 inches. Eight tenths of an inch of new snow had fallen since 1 pm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A coastal storm passing southern New England just southeast of Nantucket resulted in a period of snow across northern Massachusetts and southwest New Hampshire.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four to nine inches of snow fell across western and central Hillsborough County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Unseasonably warm temperatures moved into southern New England ahead of a cold front which allowed for excellent atmospheric mixing.  This resulted in strong to damaging winds across much of eastern Massachusetts and Rhode Island.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A weather station at an amateur radio operator's home in Barnstable recorded a wind gust of 67 mph.  Also in Barnstable, a tree was downed on Long Pond Road.  The Automated Weather Observing System at Cape Cod Coast Guard Air Station (KFMH) recorded a wind gust of 58 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Although this lake effect event produced ���marginal��� snowfall amounts, the snows were accompanied by winds gusting to 35 mph. The blowing snow resulted in significantly reduced visibilities that affected the morning and afternoon commute periods.  Lake snows first developed in a southwest flow ahead of an approaching cold front. Activity had just about ended before another area of general light snow moved across the Lower Lakes late Wednesday (27th) night followed by a sharper cold front. This snow was enhanced dramatically overnight into Thursday morning off Lake Erie on a southwest flow again. A more typical west northwest flow set up Thursday afternoon in the wake of the front with several strong but transitional bands with upstream connections dropping across the northern counties. |Specific snowfall totals off Lake Ontario for the event included: 18��� at Hooker; 14��� at Redfield; 11��� at Highmarket and Harrisville; 10��� at Theresa; and 8��� at Watertown.  Off Lake Erie, the reports included:  12��� in south Buffalo and Mayville, 11��� at Lancaster; 10��� at Alden, North Tonawanda, and the Buffalo International Airport.

A strong cold front crossed the region on New Year���s Day. A broad area of lake effect snows develop along the south shores of Lakes Erie and Ontario late on the first. Some narrow intense bands developed in this area and extended up to twenty miles inland. The activity continued through Saturday (3rd) and then strengthened in place Saturday Night as a large area of moisture spiraled around a massive coastal storm off New England.  A general burst of moderate to heavy snow accompanied this synoptic feature as it dropped south and southwest across the entire region during Sunday, then finally the lake effect weakened and retreated to near the lakes again Sunday night.  This event was unique in many ways, most notably in the large amounts of snow off Lake Ontario back across much of the Niagara frontier. A general one to two feet fell over two days, with up to 30 inches around Niagara Falls. Another area of very heavy snow focused on Wayne to Oswego County where two to three feet fell. The Rochester area caught a bit less, but still up to 18 inches near the Lake.  Off Lake Erie, two feet or more fell near Chautauqua Lake from Mayville to Jamestown. |Specific snowfall totals Off Lake Erie included:  Mayville 31���; Jamestown 28���; and Perrysburg 26���. Off Lake Ontario, the reports included: 42��� at Fulton; 38��� at Lacona; 36��� at Marion; 34��� at Scriba; 32��� at Hannibal; 31��� at Niagara Falls; 30��� at Pulaski; 26��� at North Tonawanda, Kent and Williamson; 24��� at Lockport; 22��� at Oswego; 19��� at North Amherst; 16��� at Perry; 14��� at Tonawanda; and 9��� to 18��� in Rochester (from north to south across the city).

On the afternoon of February 23rd through the evening hours of February 24th, the combination of a large developing upper atmospheric low pressure system across the lower Great Lakes and Ohio River Valley with a surface low south of New England accounted for a prolonged fetch of sub-tropical Atlantic moisture to feed back into marginally cold air across New England and New York.||A heavy wet snow fell across the eastern Adirondacks and Champlain Valley of New York that resulted in snowfall accumulations of 6 to 18 inches with the higher amounts within the Champlain Valley. The weight of the heavy snow accounted for scattered power outages across the region.||Some specific snowfall totals include; 22.5 inches in Ticonderoga (Essex county), 17 inches in Peru (Clinton county), 15 inches in Schuyler Falls (Clinton county), 7 inches in Newcomb and Lake Placid (Essex county) with 6 inches in Malone and Tupper Lake (Franklin county).

Widespread dense fog affected much of central and south-central Kansas during the predawn hours on the 22nd. Visibilities were one-quarter mile or less. One truck accident was reported in Kingman county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Poor visibility in dense fog caused a trucker to drive his rig off the road and onto diagonally-oriented railroad tracks for one-quarter mile, causing damage to the tires and rims. No one was injured. The incident occurred about one mile west of Cunningham on Highway 54 westbound. Property damage amounts are rough estimates. The Kingman Leader-Courier contributed to this report.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Heavy rains that fell across portions of Minnesota and Wisconsin in the middle part of September produced considerable flooding on many tributaries of the Mississippi River. As this water moved downstream and into the Mississippi, it pushed the river out of its banks during the last part of September.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rains in the middle part of September across parts of Minnesota and Wisconsin produced flooding along the Mississippi River at Guttenberg. The river exceeded the flood stage from September 29th through the remainder of the month, but did not crest until early October.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A relatively weak, but tightly wrapped low pressure system moved into the far northeast Pacific ocean during the morning hours on January 13, 2010.  An occluded front associated with this system swept north across western Oregon, bringing some high winds to the central Oregon coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Amateur radio equipment in Gleneden Beach (located about 20 miles north of Newport, Oregon) measured a peak wind gust of 70 mph.||Additionally, the Oregon department of transportation equipment on the Yaquina Bay bridge in Newport, Oregon, measured sustained winds of 40 to 42mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong storm system tracking northeast from the Gulf of Mexico spread heavy snow and freezing rain into Central North Carolina the evening of January 29th. The snow continued into the morning hours of January 30th. Between 5 to 10 inches of snow blanketed areas along and north of Highway 64 with up to a foot of snow reported along the Virginia border. Locations across the southern piedmont, southern coastal plain and sandhills experienced a mix of snow and freezing rain. Freezing rain accumulations ranged from one-eighth to a half inch of ice.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 2 to 4 inches of snow fell across the county in addition to a trace of freezing rain.  Several vehicle accidents and a number of power outages were reported. Due to the cold temperatures icy road conditions persisted for several days resulting in the closure of schools and businesses.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front brought rain and high winds to northern Connecticut.  Winds knocked numerous trees and wires down in Hartford and Tolland counties.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees and wires were downed throughout Hartford County.  This included trees in Glastonbury, Manchester, West Hartford, Berlin, Suffield, Farmington, East Hartford, Granby, Windsor, Wethersfield, Southington, Simsbury, and South Windsor.  Trees fell on houses on Lincoln Street in Berlin, on Evergreen Lane in Glastonbury, and on Grennan Road in West Hartford.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread light to moderate snow fell during the daylight hours of January 7th as an Alberta Clipper tracked through the region.  Snowfall amounts generally ranged between 4 and 6 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Light snow developed just before daybreak on January 7th and became moderate to heavy  during the morning and early afternoon hours as a clipper system moved through the region.  The snow tapered off to just a few lingering snow showers and flurries by late in the afternoon.  Total snow accumulations of 5 to 6 inches were common across the county, with isolated heavier amounts reported.  The accumulating snow and low visibilities led to a few accidents and slide-offs across the area, along with cancellations of local events.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: By late afternoon of July 17th, an area of low pressure was located over the far southern Red River Valley with a warm front extending to its east. Temperatures had topped out in the middle 80s with dew points in the lower 70s. Thunderstorms flared up along and north of the warm front, mainly affecting southeast North Dakota and west central Minnesota. Large hail was reported along with a few strong winds gusts. Heavy amounts of rain also fell along the Highway 10 corridor in west central Minnesota, mainly between Detroit Lakes and Wadena.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A surface trough moved into west central Minnesota during the late afternoon and early evening of the 10th, helping to initiate thunderstorms. Temperatures in this area had risen into the low to mid 80s with dew points in the mid to upper 60s.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A brief tornado touchdown was viewed in the open fields about one mile west of the Wadena Airport (KADC).  Maximum winds speed were estimated to 80 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A potent and slow moving area of low pressure dumped heavy rainfall on portions of eastern Kentucky on January 24th and 25th. The result for quite a few locations east of I-75 was flooded and washed out roads. Numerous roads in the affected counties had to be closed for varying periods of time due to flood water or damaged caused to the roads by the flood water.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A car was trapped on a flooded road in East Bernstadt.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Abundant rain advanced north into the region in advance of an area of low pressure to the west while a frontal boundary remained draped over the region. An average of 2 to 5 inches of rain fell from this system onto an already saturated ground from recent snow melt and rainfall. The heavy rain contributed to widespread flash flooding, mudslides, areal flooding, and river flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flash flooding caused Wolf Island Road to be closed due to flowing water. There were two locations in Rockingham County where swift water rescues were needed.  Damage values are estimated.

With below normal precipitation during the month of December, ongoing drought conditions persisted across a portion of Central Alabama through the month of December. The hardest hit area continues to be portions of eastern Alabama, from extreme eastern Elmore county and extreme northern Macon county northeastward across portions of Lee, Tallapoosa, and Chambers counties, where Extreme (D3) drought conditions were identified by the U.S. Drought Monitor.

A strong storm system tracking northeast from the Gulf of Mexico spread heavy snow and freezing rain into Central North Carolina the evening of January 29th. The snow continued into the morning hours of January 30th. Between 5 to 10 inches of snow blanketed areas along and north of Highway 64 with up to a foot of snow reported along the Virginia border. Locations across the southern piedmont, southern coastal plain and sandhills experienced a mix of snow and freezing rain. Freezing rain accumulations ranged from one-eighth to a half inch of ice.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 5 to 7 inches of snow fell across the county.  Several vehicle accidents and scattered power outages were reported. Due to the cold temperatures icy road conditions persisted for several days resulting in the closure of schools and businesses.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Light to moderate snow and strong winds resulted in low visibilities and drifting snow February 5th into early February 6th, as a rapidly intensifying area of low pressure tracked eastward through the lower Ohio Valley. Snowfall totals generally ranged between 4 and 8 inches, with drifts as high as 3 to 4 feet.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Light to moderate snow developed during morning hours of February 5th, and continued into the early morning hours of February 6th.  Gusty winds accompanied the snow, with gusts of 40 to 50 mph limiting visibilities.  The falling snow and strong winds also led to plenty of blowing and drifting snow, with drifts of 2 to 4 feet reported.  Snowfall amounts of 5 to 8 inches were common across the county, with many country roads drifted shut.  There were also reports of slide-offs and accidents across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The first significant snow storm of the 2010-11 winter season dumped between 2 and 12 inches of snow on eastern Kentucky on December 12th and 13th. The highest snowfall totals occurred in Bell, Lee, and Leslie, and McCreary counties where 10-12 inches were reported. There were several culprits for this snow event, as areas of low pressure moving across the lower Great Lakes and up the eastern slopes of the Appalachian Mountains combined forces over the Ohio and Tennessee valleys. The highest snowfall totals occurred along the Kentucky River basin as an intense band of moderate to heavy snowfall remained in place there during the overnight hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An NWS employee reported that 9.8 inches of snow had fallen in Beattyville, with 3.3 inches of new snow since 7 am.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A series of strong weather systems brought heavy rain to northwest Oregon causing flooding on local rivers.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rainfall over the area caused the Pudding River to overflow its banks and flood farmland.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Between the evening of the 30th and the morning of the 31st, two separate lines of thunderstorms produced significant severe weather across southwest Missouri including damaging wind, large hail, and deadly tornadoes. The first round of storms lifted out of Arkansas late on the evening of the 30th and the second round moved out of western Kansas shortly before daybreak on the 31st.

Record Snowfall occurred across the greater Burlington area on January 2nd into January 3rd.||A powerful ocean storm southeast of Nova Scotia during the late afternoon of January 2nd, retrograded into the Gulf of Maine near Rockport, Maine by the morning of January 3rd and then proceeded to return to the Atlantic Ocean during the afternoon of January 3rd.||Wraparound snows moved into northern Vermont during the afternoon and evening hours of January 2nd and continued through the afternoon of January 3rd. The windward side (west) of the various mountain ranges in Vermont witnessed the heaviest snowfall due to upslope conditions with the leeward side (east) received less snow due to downslope. In addition, some training of mesoscale snow bands, likely a result of upslope and convergence within the Champlain Valley of Vermont accounted for record snowfall in the Burlington area. ||Favorable upslope regions received 8 to 18 inches of snowfall with over 30 inches in the greater Burlington area. Meanwhile downslope regions received 2 to 6 inches of snowfall. In addition, brisk northwest winds of 15 to 25 mph with higher gusts caused considerable blowing and drfiting of the snow with 4 to 5 foot snow drifts reported.||A record 33.1 inches of snow fell with this storm at Burlington Int'l Airport in South Burlington, which surpassed the old record of 29.8 inches that occurred on December 25-28 in 1969. ||Some other specific snowfall totals; 30 inches in Essex Junction and Colchester (Chittenden county), 25 inches in Monkton (Addison county) and Milton (Chittenden county), 24 inches in Charlotte (Chittenden county), 22 inches in Jeffersonville (Lamoille county), Underhill and Jericho (Chittenden county), 18 inches in Canaan (Essex county) and Sheldon Springs (Franklin county), 16 inches in Cambridge (Lamoille county), 14 inches in Barton (Orleans county), Danby (Rutland county) and Lincoln (Addison county).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An intense lake effect snow band set up across far north-central Indiana during the afternoon hours of January 1st. This band continued into the early morning hours of January 2nd, with a few locations receiving more than a foot of fluffy snow accumulation.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy lake effect snow fell during the afternoon and early evening hours of January 1st, before tapering off to lighter snow showers and flurries by early January 2nd.  Snowfall rates of 1 to 3 inches per hour were common, with snowfall accumulations generally ranging between 2 and 6 inches.  A trained spotter reported 6 inches of snow accumulation in Jimtown.  Gusty winds accompanied the heavy snow, which resulted in numerous reports of visibilities near zero and drifting snow.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: EM reported 4-6 inches of snow across the county.
